{[%csl Ra2,Ga3,Gb4,Re4][%cal Gb4e4,Gh8a1] Sometimes, especially against weak
opposition, Black can generate a tremendous piece pressure at a very early stage
of the game. This usually happens when White failed to establish a queenside
blockade (we will examine a different kind of blockades later) and the "a" and
"b" files are available for Black's heavy pieces. In positions in which White
had played b2-b3 or a2-a3, Black's task is even simpler since he can make use
of the weakened squares a3 or b3.  On the diagram, we can see some kind of a
model position. Black's heavy pieces are placed in the best possible way. The
pawns on a2 and e4 are under pressure. Additionally, Black has managed to
exchange one of his knights and his bishop is without opposition. Another
problem that White usually faces in Benko is the unstable c3-knight. This
problem becomes even more evident when White's dark-squared bishop is not on
the board. Black can already consider increasing the pressure with ...c5-c4
followed by ...Nc5.}  *

