{ Black's queen and rooks put a lof of pressure on the queenside.
Since White has played b2-b3, the c3-knight is unstable. Also, in many cases,
White should reckon with ...c5-c4. In this position, one of White's ideas is
Qc2 followed by Bd2, a2-a4, and Nb5. That is why Black went for the precise} 
15... h6 $1 {Black is trying to eliminate the important dark-squared bishop
which can stabilize White's queenside.} 16. Bxf6 ({It is not possible to keep
the bishop. For example:} 16. Bf4 g5 17. Bg3 ({nothing changes} 17. Be3 Ng4)
17... Nh5 {Black manages to eliminate the bishop.}) 16... Bxf6 17. Ne2 $6 {
White is planning to transfer his f3-knight to c4 after the eventual exchange
of the queens. Black, however, is not forced to go for this exchange. At the
same time, the e2-knight would remain rather passive.} ({A bit more active
would be} 17. Na4 {when Black's best is} Rb4 {[%cal Gc5c4] White should
already take ...c5-c4 into consideration.} 18. a3 R4b5 19. Qc2 Ne5 $1 {A very
important positional move. When White had played b2-b3 and a2-a3, Black should
try to exchange the knights. In such a case, the pressure on b3 turns out to
be decisive.} {The natural} 20. Nd2 {is well met by} c4 $1 {when after} 21. b4
({Safer is} 21. Nxc4 Qc7 22. Rfc1 Nxc4 23. Qxc4 Qxc4 24. Rxc4 Rxb3 25. Rxb3
Rxb3 {with an equal position.}) 21... Qa7 22. Ra1 Rc8 23. Nc3 Rb7 $36 {[%cal
Ge5d3] Black maintains his queenside pressure.}) 17... Qa3 $1 {This move which
fixes the a2-pawn is an important part of Black's dark-squared strategy. Had
the White's dark-squared bishop been on the board, White could have chased the
queen away with Bc1.} 18. Rfc1 Rb4 $1 {Another important move. Black makes use
of the vulnerable e4-pawn.} 19. Qc2 $2 {This move is an obvious mistake.} ({
White should have protected the a2-pawn with} 19. Rc2 {when after} Rxe4 20.
Qxh6 Reb4 {[%cal Gc5c4]} 21. Rbc1 {the position remains balanced.}) 19... Ra8 {
[%csl Ra2] It turns out that there is no way to protect the a2-pawn.} 20. Nc3
Bxc3 21. Qxc3 Rxe4 {Black is strategically winning. The material is equal but
White has a terrible pawn structure.} 22. h3 Nf6 23. Rd1 Re2 0-1

