{ Besides his
strong pawn center, White has established his typical queenside blockade. The
only drawback of his position is the lack of development. Therefore, Black
should act energetically. As usual, his queenside counterplay starts with} 
14... c4 15. Qc2 Nc5 $1 {Well-timed pawn sacrifice. Black should prevent his
opponent from completing the development. If given enough time, White would
play Ne2 and castle. Later on, he can even think of occupying the c6-square
with the maneuver Ned4-c6.} 16. Qxc4 Nfd7 $1 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gd7e5] Another
precise move. Depending on White's reaction, the knight can go to b6 or e5.}
17. Bc3 Nb6 $6 {Black wants to start regaining material as soon as possible,
Nevertheless, chasing the queen away from its vulnerable position was not the
optimal decision.} ({I think that better was} 17... Qb7 {[%cal Gf8c8]
preparing ...Rfc8. In this way, Black brings his last inactive piece into play.
}) 18. Qe2 Nbxa4 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Nh3 $2 {This is a mistake. White should
have prevented the idea ...Nb3.} ({The computer considers the position to be
equal. From a practical point of view, however, White's play is very difficult.
Maybe, the best he can do is} 20. b4 Nd7 21. Nh3 ({The attempt to develop the
knight via e2 with} 21. Qd2 {is also possible but a bit riskier. Black can
follow with} Ne5 22. Ne2 Nc5 $1 23. Rxa8 Ncd3+ 24. Kf1 Qxa8 25. g3 f5 $36 {
Once again, the machine affirms that the position is balanced. Nevertheless,
the vulnerable white king creates a lot of practical difficulties.}) {Here, I
have analyzed the following sequence:} 21... Qb7 22. O-O Qb6+ 23. Nf2 Rfb8 24.
Na3 Qxb4 {Quite often, in Benko structures, even the symmetrical positions are
not easy for White due to the activity of Black's pieces. The a3-knight is
rather unstable. White's best try would be} 25. Qc4 {provoking the exchange of
the queen. The game can continue} Nc3 26. Qxb4 Rxb4 27. Nc2 Ne2+ 28. Kh1 Rba4
29. Rxa4 Rxa4 $15 {Despite the exchange of the queens, Black retains some
pressure because his pieces are more active and can easily invade White's camp.
This structure is very typical for Benko. Note that, White can even lose such
positions if he does not manage to coordinate his pieces.}) 20... Nb3 21. Ra3
Nc1 $6 {This is a step in the wrong direction.} ({Critical was} 21... Qc1+ 22.
Qd1 Nxb2 23. Qxc1 Nd3+ 24. Kd1 Ndxc1 {Once again, Black keeps pressing in this
symmetrical structure.}) 22. Qd2 Qc4 23. Qd4+ Qxd4 24. Nxd4 Nxb2 {Again, we
have a symmetrical position, but this time White's pieces are better placed in
comparison to the previous line.} 25. Rc3 Ncd3+ 26. Kd2 Ne5 27. Rhc1 Na4 28.
Rc7 Nc5 $1 {[%cal Gf8b8,Gb8b2] Black closes the c-file and prepares ...Rfb8-b2.
Meanwhile, the last move creates an interesting trap.} 29. Rxe7 $2 {White runs
into the trap.} ({The move} 29. Rc2 {was safe enough.}) 29... Rfc8 $1 {[%csl
Re7][%cal Gg7f8,Gg7f6] It turns out that the e7-rook is trapped. Black is
planning to follow with 30...Kf8 or ...30...Kf6.} 30. f4 Kf8 31. Rxe5 dxe5 32.
fxe5 Nxe4+ 33. Kd1 Nc3+ 34. Kd2 Nxd5 35. Rxc8+ Rxc8 36. Nf2 Ra8 37. Ke2 Ra4 38.
Kd3 Nf4+ 0-1

