{[#]In positions, where Black's pieces are active and the g7-bishop is
unopposed, White's extra a-pawn is not very important. Additionally, White has
his typical problem related to unstable c3-knight.  At this point,
Naroditsky went for the precise} 20... Rbb4 {putting pressure on the e4-pawn.
Black is planning to strengthen the pressure by employing the manoeuvre
Nf6-d7-c5.} 21. Rb1 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]} 22. Rxb4 Rxb4 23. a5 Nc5 24. Qc2 Qa6 {
[%cal Ga6c4] The queen is usually well placed on the diagonal a6-f1. Black's
immediate idea is ...Qc4. Therefore, White played} 25. Nd2 Bd4 {Black has
fully activated his pieces. Even though the computer claims equality,
practically speaking, Black's play is a lot easier. White can easily go wrong
in such positions.} 26. Nd1 $2 {This is already a mistake. The black queen
shouldn't have been allowed to invade the e2-square.} ({White's best was} 26.
Nf3 {when the following line is possible:} Bf6 27. Qe2 Bxc3 28. Qxa6 Nxa6 29.
Rxc3 Rxe4 30. Re3 $1 Ra4 31. Rxe7 h6 $11 {with a draw.}) 26... Qe2 27. Ra2 Nd3
$2 {This tempting move actually lets the advantage disappear.} ({A normal move
such as} 27... Kg7 {would leave White in some kind of a zugzwang.}) 28. Nf3 $1
Qxc2 29. Rxc2 Bc5 30. Rc3 $2 {We see how easy one makes mistakes in these
positions.} ({White should have preferred} 30. Nd2 {when after} Ra4 31. Kf1
Rxa5 32. Nb3 Ra3 {the position is equal but Black still retains at least some
small pressure.}) 30... Nf4 {[%cal Gf4e2,Gb4e4] Black is threatening both 31...
Ne2+ and 31...Rxe4. After taking the e4-pawn Black is winning since White's
structure is collapsing.} 31. Kh2 Rxe4 32. Rb3 Ra4 33. Rb5 Nxd5 $19 34. Nb2 Rb4
35. Rxb4 Bxb4 36. a6 Nc7 37. Nd4 Bc3 38. Nc6 Bxb2 39. a7 Kf8 40. Kg3 Ke8 41.
Kg4 Kd7 42. Nb4 Bd4 0-1

