{[#] In positions where White has already played b2-b3, the advance c5-c4
often weakens the a4-pawn. Sometimes, after simplifications, White manages to
retain the a4-pawn. Nevertheless, the activity of Black's pieces usually
compensates the pawn. There are many empty squares on the queenside and for
White is very difficult to keep Black's counterplay under control. The
following game is a typical example. In this position, Black went for
simplifications with} 20... c4 $1 {The following moves are more or less forced:
} 21. bxc4 Qxc4 22. Rfc1 Rc8 23. Qxc4 Rxc4 24. Rxc4 Nxc4 25. Nbc3 {We have
reached a typical Benko endgame. White's extra pawn is compensated by the
activity of Black's minor pieces. In such positions, the unstable c3-knight is
one of Black's main sources of counterplay. Therefore, in the game, Leon Hoyos
played} Rc8 26. Rb4 $6 {This move allows Black to further activate his pieces.}
({More to the point was} 26. Ra1 Na5 27. Ra3 {restricting Black's immediate
ideas. On the other hand, it is now clear how White will be making progress.
Black can already consider bringing his king to the queenside.}) 26... Nd2 27.
Nb5 Rc2 {Black managed to invade White's camp and now his counterplay is
sufficient.} 28. f4 g5 {Not a bad move but not the most technical one.} ({
In my opinion, simpler would be} 28... h4 {[%csl Rg2] fixing the g2-pawn.}) 29.
fxg5 Bxg5 30. Kf2 Bf6 $2 {This is already a mistake after which White should
be winning.} ({The most precise continuation was} 30... Bh4+ 31. g3 Bf6 {
Having provoked g2-g3, Black can answer} 32. Ke1 {with} Nf3+) 31. Ke1 $1 {
Suddenly, White is winning since the mobility of the rook and the knight is
restricted. Actually, the knight is almost trapped. White threatens 32.Kd1 Ra2
32.Nbc3, winning a piece. The following few moves are more or less forced.} Nc4
32. Nbd4 Bxd4 33. Nxd4 Rc1+ 34. Ke2 Kg7 35. Nc6 {The a-pawn is about to become
unstoppable. Therefore, Black is forced to sacrifice the e7-pawn by playing}
Ne5 36. Nxe5 $6 {Strangely enough, White does not accept the sacrifice.} ({
In the variation,} 36. Nxe7 Rc2+ 37. Ke3 Rxg2 38. Nf5+ Kf6 39. Nxd6 Rh2 40. Rb1
Rxh3+ 41. Kd4 Rd3+ 42. Kc5 {White should be winning.}) 36... dxe5 37. Kd2 $6 {
This passive move does not fit into the spirit of the rook endgames.} ({
Of course, the position is complicated and required analysis. I believe that
with a precise play White should be winning. One of my lines goes} 37. Kd3 {
The king is heading for the queenside.} h4 38. Rb7 Kf6 39. a5 Ra1 40. Ra7 {
Black's king is stacked to the e7-pawn. That's why Black's kingside counterplay
is rather slow.} Ra3+ 41. Kc4 Re3 42. Ra6+ Kg5 43. Rb6 Rxe4+ 44. Kb5 Rd4 45. d6
$1 {An elegant decision. Now, the rook cannot stop White's passer.} exd6 46. a6
Rd5+ 47. Ka4 $1 Rd1 48. Rb3 $18 {White will promote his pawn.}) 37... Rg1 38.
Kc3 Rxg2 39. Rb3 $2 {This move gives Black enough counterplay for a draw.} ({
Better would have been} 39. Rb2 $1 Rg1 ({Another logical line is} 39... Rg3+
40. Kb4 Rxh3 41. a5 Re3 42. a6 Rxe4+ 43. Kb5 Rd4 44. a7 Rxd5+ 45. Ka4 Rd8 46.
Rb8 Rd1 47. a8=Q Ra1+ 48. Kb3 Rxa8 49. Rxa8 Kf6 50. Kc3 Kg5 51. Kd3 f5 52. Ke3
$18 {White is winning. Both his pieces participate in the fight against the
pawns.}) 40. Ra2 {with a simple win. Black is not in time with his counterplay.
} f5 41. exf5 Kf6 42. a5 Kxf5 43. a6 Rg8 44. a7 Ra8 45. Ra4 e4 46. Kd4 Kf4 47.
Kc5 Kf3 48. Kc6 e3 49. Kb7 e2 50. Ra1 Rh8 51. a8=Q Rxa8 52. Kxa8 Kf2 53. Kb7
$18) 39... f5 40. a5 fxe4 41. Kb4 Kf6 42. Ra3 Rb2+ 43. Kc5 Rc2+ 44. Kb6 Rb2+
45. Kc6 Rc2+ 46. Kd7 Rd2 47. a6 Rxd5+ 48. Kc6 Rd6+ 49. Kc7 Rd3 50. Ra1 Rc3+ 51.
Kb7 Rb3+ 52. Kc6 Rc3+ ({At the point, the simplest way to the draw would have
been} 52... Rb8 53. a7 Ra8 {The idea is to provoke} 54. Kb7 {when the white
king is far away from the e4-pawn. The rest is simple and forced.} Rxa7+ 55.
Kxa7 Kg5 56. Kb6 Kf4 57. h4 e3 58. Kc6 Kf3 59. Kd7 e2 60. Kxe7 Kf2 61. Ke6 e1=Q
62. Rxe1 Kxe1 63. Kxe5 Ke2 64. Kf5 Kf3 65. Kg5 Ke4 66. Kxh5 Kf5 $11) 53. Kd5
Kf5 $4 {This is a blunder.} ({A simple solution was} 53... Rc8 54. Kxe4 Ke6 $11
{with a draw.}) 54. a7 e6+ 55. Kd6 Rc8 56. a8=Q Rxa8 57. Rxa8 Kf4 58. Ra5 h4
59. Kxe6 1-0

