{[%csl Rb2,Rd3,Rf3][%cal Gf6g4,Gg4e5,Ge5d3,Gc5c4,Gb8b2,Gd3b2,Gg7b2,Ga6f1] THE
MANEUVER ...NG4-E5 The manoeuvre...Ng4-e5 is very typical for the Benko
structures. There are three main ideas behind this manoeuvre: 1) Install the
knight on d3 and follow with ...c5-c4, thus achieving the perfect construction
2) Occupy the c4-square with the knight 3) Exchange a pair of knights by
challenging White's f3-knight. Of course, quite often, these ideas are combined.
For example, let's take a look at the model position on the diagram. By playing
...Ng4-e5, Black will try to exchange the e5 knight (after this exchange, the
d7-knight will occupy the e5-square. At the same time, depending on the
circumstances, Black can play either ...Nd3 or ...Nc4. It is important to
mention that in such positions, the black queen is perfectly placed on a6.}  *

