{[#] Black managed to achieve a very comfortable position since White failed
to establish his typical queenside blockade (a4+Nb5). It is clear that Black's
heavy pieces have occupied perfect positions. Now, its time to find the
perfect arrangement for the minor pieces. Black went for the typical} 15... Ng4
$1 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gg4e5,Ge5d3] By means of this typical manoeuvre Black is
fighting for the key d3-square. Of course, the knight's jump to d3 can be
supported with ...c5-c4. Also, by playing ...Nge5, Black wants to exchange a
pair of knights which is always very favourable for him in Benko structures.}
16. a4 {[%cal Gc3b5] White is trying to establish his knight on b5.} Qc4 {
The idea of this move is to prevent 17.Nb5 and the take the important
b3-square under control.} ({Nevertheless, I think that more natural would have
been} 16... Nge5 17. Nxe5 Nxe5 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Ga6d3] White cannot prevent
Black from occupying the d3-square. Besides the typical ...Nd3, Black can
start with ...Qd3 and install the knight after the exchange of the queens. As
we have pointed out in the introduction, in Benko Gambit, the exchange of the
queens usually favours Black.} {Of course, impossible is} 18. Nb5 $4 {due to}
Rxb5 19. axb5 Qxa1 20. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 21. Bc1 Bh6 $19 {and Black is winning.}) 17.
h3 {A waste of time.} ({More constructive would have been} 17. Rec1 {with the
idea to follow with Nd1. After the exchange of the queens, White can
neutralize the pressure along the long diagonal with Bc3. Another idea would
be to sacrifice the b2-pawn and start pushing the a-pawn.} Nge5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5
19. Nd1 Qa6 20. a5 Nd3 21. Rcb1 {Black keeps his typical queenside pressure,
but White is not worse. The a5-pawn is an important asset.}) 17... Nge5 18.
Nxe5 Nxe5 {[%cal Ge5d3]} 19. Re3 Qa6 $1 {[%cal Ge5c4,Gc5c4,Ge5d3] A key move.
Black is creating two threats - the direct ...Nc4 and the positional ...c5-c4
followed by ...Nd3.} 20. Bc1 ({Another option is} 20. b3 {when Black should
play} c4 $1 21. Rb1 cxb3 22. Rxb3 Rc8 {[%cal Ge5c4,Ga6a4] With a typical
queenside pressure.}) 20... c4 {[%cal Ge5d3]} 21. Ra3 {[%cal Gc3b5] A smart
idea. White covers the b3-square and prepares 22.Nb5. Despite the fact that
Black's play is a lot easier, the position is objectively equal.} Bh6 ({
The thematic} 21... Nd3 {could be met with} 22. Nb5 {when Black should opt for
the following sequence:} Qc8 23. Bd2 Bxb2 24. Raxd3 cxd3 25. Qxb2 Qc4 26. Qc3
Rxa4 27. Qxc4 Rxc4 28. Nc3 Rb2 29. Rxd3 Rxd2 30. Rxd2 Rxc3 $11 {with a draw.})
22. Re2 Bxc1 23. Qxc1 Nd3 24. Qg5 Nxb2 $2 {Black shouldn't have taken the pawn
without taking care of the defence of the e7-pawn. Now, White is better.} ({
Better was} 24... f6 25. Qe3 Nxb2 {when the position is objectively equal but
Black's play is easier.}) 25. Qxe7 Nd3 26. Qg5 $6 {A pointless move.} ({
White should have played} 26. Qf6 {with the idea to answer} Rb3 {with} 27. Ra1
{keeping everything under control. Black does not have enough compensation for
the pawn.}) 26... Rb3 $1 {Now, Black's counterplay is getting very dangerous.
From a practical point of view, for White is very difficult to defend this
position} 27. Rea2 Qb6 28. Qd2 $2 {This is the decisive mistake after which
Black is winning.} ({The only move was} 28. Kh2 {when Black should play} Qc5 {
with a better position.}) 28... Qb4 29. Rxb3 cxb3 30. Ra1 Rc8 31. Nb1 Rc1+ 0-1

