{[#] White has managed to establish a typical queenside blockade (a4+ Nb5).
Black has two ways to fight against this construction: 1) ...c5-c4 followed by
a knight transfer to d3 2) exchange the b5-knight by means of the manoeuvre
Ne8-c7 Obviously, the first method does not work in this position since White
has good control of the c4-square. Therefore, Black went for} 14... Ne8 $1 {
[%cal Ge8c7] preparing the exchange of the knight. After such an exchange, the
pressure along the b-file would be combined with the power of the g7-bishop.
That's why White decided to neutralize the bishop with} 15. Bc3 Nc7 16. Bxg7
Kxg7 {It becomes clear that White cannot support his knight. Black is
threatening 17...Nxb5 followed by ...Qxa1. That's why White's} 17. h4 $6 {
does not make sense.} ({More precise is} 17. Ra3 {when the critical position
arises after} Nxb5 18. axb5 Qb6 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 {[%cal Ga8a5] If Black manages
to eliminate the b5-pawn with 20...Ra5 followed by ...Rxb5, he would be better
thanks to the superior pawn structure. Therefore, White should play
energetically:} 20. b4 {The following sequence seems pretty straightforward:}
cxb4 21. Qb2+ Nf6 22. Qxb4 Qa5 23. Qb2 Qa2 24. Qxa2 Rxa2 25. Rb1 Nxe4 26. b6
Nc5 $11 {Black is just in time to block the b-pawn. The position is equal.})
17... Nxb5 18. axb5 Qxa1 19. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 20. Kh2 f6 $1 {A typical Benko move
which is often played after the exchange of the dark-squared bishops. Black is
preventing the advance e4-e5. Now, the threat is 21...Ra5. The position
remains balanced but Black's play is a bit easier.} 21. b4 $1 {By deflecting
the c5-pawn, White opens the c-file for the queen and frees the d4-square for
the knight.} Ra4 22. e5 $5 {With this creative move, White is trying the
weaken the kingside and to create space for his pieces.} ({Objectively
speaking, better would have been the conservative} 22. bxc5 Nxc5 23. Qb2 Rxe4
24. g3 {when the position remains balanced.}) 22... fxe5 23. bxc5 Nxc5 24. h5
Rf4 25. Qb2 {[%cal Gf3e5] Creating the threat of 26.Nxe5.} Rf5 26. hxg6 hxg6
27. Kg1 Kf7 28. Qb4 $6 {This is an inaccuracy. The queen should have stayed on
b2 in order to discourage ideas based on ...e5-e4.} ({A possible option would
be} 28. b6 {with the idea} e4 29. Nd4 Rxd5 $4 30. Nc6 $18 {White is winning
since the black rook does not have the h8-square.}) 28... e4 29. Nd4 Rxd5 30.
Qc4 ({In this position,} 30. Nc6 $2 {is well met by} Rh8 {with a huge
advantage for Black.}) 30... e6 31. g3 Ra8 32. Nc6 $2 {This is already a
mistake. Now, White's king is vulnerable.} ({White has many ways to keep the
position balanced. One of them would have been} 32. b6) 32... Ra1+ 33. Kg2 Rh5
{Black is already going for mating ideas.} 34. Nd8+ Ke8 $2 {This move spoils
the advantage.} ({After} 34... Ke7 35. Nc6+ Ke8 {[%csl Rg2][%cal Ga1h1,Gh5h1]
Black is winning.}) {After this mistake, the game is over.} 35. Nxe6 $4 ({
White missed the elegant} 35. Nb7 {after which Black must be precise in order
to maintain the balance. A possible continuation would be} Rah1 36. Nxd6+ Ke7
37. Nxe4 R1h2+ 38. Kf1 Nxe4 39. Qxe4 Rxb5 40. Kg1 {The position is equal.})
35... Rhh1 $19 36. f3 Rag1+ 37. Kf2 Rf1+ 38. Ke2 exf3+ 39. Ke3 Re1+ 40. Kxf3
Rxe6 41. Qd5 Rf1+ 42. Kg2 Rb1 43. Qc6+ Nd7 44. Qd5 Rb2+ 45. Kh3 Ke7 46. Qg5+
Rf6 47. Qe3+ Ne5 48. Qa7+ Ke6 49. Qb8 g5 50. Qe8+ Kf5 51. Qc8+ Ke4 52. Qb7+ d5
53. Qh7+ Ke3 54. Qa7+ Ke4 55. Qh7+ Kf3 56. g4 Rg2 57. b6 Rg3+ 58. Kh2 Nxg4+ 59.
Kh1 Nf2+ 0-1

