{POSITIONS WITH A PAWN ON B5 This structure which arises after the exchange of
the bishops on b5 is the most important type of position for our repertoire.
The b5-pawn closes the b-file and gives White a lot of space on the queenside.
In this way, the pawn restricts the activity of Black's heavy pieces. In some
positions, however, the b5-pawn turns out to be a weakness. Black usually puts
pressure on the pawn by means of Rfb8 and Qb6 followed by Ne8-c7. Sometimes,
Black can even give his dark-squared bishop for the c3-knight in order to take
the pawn. When playing with a pawn on b5, White uses the following strategies:
1) Using the b5-pawn to deflect Black's pieces - In order to capture the
b5-pawn, Black wastes time. Meanwhile, White can start playing in the centre
or on the kingside. 2) Supporting the pawn and advancing it - When given the
necessary time, White can support the b5-pawn and start advancing it. In this
regards, very useful is the typical manoeuvre Nd2-c4 followed by b5-b6. The
c4-knight can also go to c6-square via a5. 3) Invading via the a-file - The
b5-pawn gives White the control of the a6-square which is a perfect outpost
for the rook. Very often White wins the battle for the a-file by means of Ra6
followed by Rfa1. If the pawn is already on b6, then White can directly go for
Ra7. In some cases, White can even sacrifice the b5-pawn in order to invade
via the a-file. In the following model games, you are going to see all these
ideas.}  *

