{[#]In this position, Black is planning to proceed with 13...Bxb5, followed by
Na6-b4, thus creating his typical queenside pressure. In order to prevent this
plan, White should recapture on b5 with a pawn. The only problem is the
unprotected a1-rook. Therefore, White played} 13. Bg5 $1 {Once again, this
typical move spoils Black's coordination. At the same time, White is preparing
the manoeuvre Nf3-d2-c4.} Re8 14. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] Another thematic idea.
After bringing the knight to c4, White can start playing in the centre and on
the kingside by means of f2-f4 and e4-e5.} {Of course, under the given
circumstances, the structure with a pawn on b5 is not favourable for Black.
Black's pieces are not coordinated and the b5-pawn is not in danger. Moreover,
Black will be forced to give the a-file. Nevertheless, other moves wouldn't
solve the problems since White's play in the centre is pretty straightforward.}
Bxb5 $6 15. axb5 Rxa1 ({Fighting for the open file with} 15... Qb7 {would not
help either:} 16. Rxa8 Qxa8 17. Nb3 $1 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gf1a1,Gb3a5,Ga5c6]
White is planning 18.Ra1 followed by Na5-c6 with a winning position.}) 16. Rxa1
Qc7 17. Nc4 Nb6 18. Nxb6 {A logical decision. White is making clear his plan
to promote the pawn. Afterwards, he can follow with the manoeuvre Qc4-a4-a7.} ({
Nevertheless, even more precise would have been} 18. Na5 {[%cal Ga5c6,Ga1a7]
with the idea of 19.Nc6 followed by Ra7.}) 18... Qxb6 19. Qc4 Nd7 $2 {Mistake
in a difficult position. Now White gains an important tempo.} ({A bit more
tenacious would have been} 19... h6 {freeing the e8-rook. Even in this case,
however, White is objectively winning. For example:} 20. Bd2 Qb7 21. Ra5 Nd7
22. Qa2 Rb8 23. Ra7 $18) 20. Ra6 Qb8 21. h3 {Of course, this prophylactic move
is not necessary but White can go for it since Black has no counterplay.} Ne5
22. Qa4 Nd3 23. b6 {The b-pawn will decide the game.} Nb4 24. Ra7 Kf8 25. b7
1-0

