{[#]We see a very typical position for the structure with a pawn on b5. Black
has the following plan at his disposal: 1) transfer the queen to b7 by means
of the manoeuvre...Qc7-b7 2) exchange all the rooks 3) attack the b5-pawn by
means of the manoeuvre...Na8-c7 (after transferring the knight to c7, Black
will play ...Bxc3 followed by taking the pawn) This plan, however, takes a lot
of time. Meanwhile, White can develop a dangerous initiative on the kingside.
Also, the b5-pawn plays an important role in the fight for the a-file since it
secures the important outpost on a6.  In the game, White played} 15. Ra6 Qc7
16. Rfa1 Qb7 {White has achieved his maximum on the queenside. Now, it is time
to create problems on the other wing. Therefore, White opted for} {The idea of
this move is to weaken Black's kingside structure by means of h4-h5 followed
by hxg6.} 17. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5]} ({Another promising continuation would have
been} 17. Bg5 {[%csl Gc6][%cal Gf3d2,Gd2b3,Gb3a5,Ga5c6] followed by the
thematic maneuver, Nd2-b3-a5-c6.}) 17... Rfb8 ({Weak is} 17... Rxa6 $2 {
because of} 18. bxa6 Qa8 19. Bg5 Re8 20. Nb5 $18 {Black's pieces are
completely tied up. At the same time, the passed a-pawn is quite dangerous.})
18. h5 Qc8 {The idea of this move is to meet} 19. Bg5 {with} Qe8 20. Bf4 {
A useful move which makes possible the advance e4-e5. Of course, this break
should be carried out under favourable circumstances.} Rxa6 21. bxa6 {
Generally speaking, this recapture is more desirable since the a-pawn becomes
quite dangerous.} ({The alternative} 21. Rxa6 {is also possible. In this case,
the b5-pawn restricts Black's queenside counterplay. At the same time, Black
is not coordinated enough to attack the pawn.}) 21... Na8 22. Ra2 {Although
not a mistake, this prophylactic was not necessary.} ({More precise would have
been} 22. e5 {Maybe, White was concerned about losing the b2-pawn after} dxe5
23. Nxe5 Nxe5 24. Bxe5 Bxe5 25. Qxe5 Rxb2 {It is obvious, however, that
Black's poor pieces and the weak king would allow White to win by force. After} 26.
Ne4 Rb8 27. a7 Rd8 28. d6 {Black can resign.}) 22... Rb4 23. Bd2 {[%cal Gc3d1]
An interesting positional idea. White wants to play 24.Nd1. Afterwards, it is
already possible to exchange Black's dark-squared bishop via c3.} Qb8 24. Nd1
Rb6 25. Ba5 Rb5 {Since Black is doomed to passivity, White does not rush.} 26.
g3 ({A bit more precise would be} 26. a7 Qb7 27. Bc3 {eliminating the pressure
along the long diagonal.}) 26... Bf6 27. Kg2 Rb3 28. Qc2 Kg7 29. Nd2 Rb5 30.
Nc3 {This move practically finishes the battle. Black is forced to part with
his bishop. Afterwards, besides being a pawn up, White also attacks on the
kingside. The position is completely winning.} Bxc3 31. Bxc3+ f6 32. Nc4 Qe8
33. Qe2 Rb8 34. Ra1 Ndb6 35. Na5 Na4 36. a7 Rb6 37. Nc6 Nxc3 38. bxc3 e6 39.
Qf3 exd5 40. exd5 Rb7 41. hxg6 hxg6 42. c4 1-0

