{ [#]Black is panning to attack the b5-pawn by means of ...
Nc7. Therefore, White should act quickly. Moiseenko played} 15. Bg5 $1 {
Once again, we see this typical idea. As we know, g5 is the perfect spot for
the bishop in such structures. Black has no satisfactory way to defend the
pawn.} Qb7 {Of course, Black avoids playing ...f7-f6. If given time, he would
chase the bishop away from the h4-d8 diagonal by playing ...h7-h6 and possibly
...g6-g5. Afterwards, he can play ...Nc7. White, however, went for} 16. b6 $1 {
[%cal Ga1a7] You can see the importance of the b-pawn. This pawn not only
deflects Black's forces but also creates important outposts on the a-file.
White is threatening Qa7 on the next move.} Nf6 17. Qa7 Qxa7 18. bxa7 Nbd7 19.
Ra1 {The pawn is unstoppable. Moiseenko wins rather quickly.} Nb6 20. Ra6 Na8
21. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4] The knight is heading for c4.} Rd8 22. Nc4 Rd7 23.
Bxf6 $1 {Not forced but the simplest. After eliminating the pressure on e4,
White is ready to follow with Na4-b6.} Bxf6 24. Na4 {[%cal Ga4b6]} 1-0

