{[#] Sometimes, even after taking the b5-pawn, Black does not solve his
problems. Let's take a look at a typical example. Black is threatening to win
the pawn back with ...Bxc3 followed by ...Qxb5. Therefore, White forces a
transition into a favourable endgame.} 19. Qa6 $1 Bxc3 20. Qxb7 Rxb7 21. bxc3
Rxb5 {This is an important typical position. This kind of endgame, with White
knight installed on c4, can be dangerous for Black. In the section, concerning
Black's ideas, we have seen that the symmetrical endings, without pawns on the
c-file, are usually favourable for Black. The presence of the pawns c3 and c5,
however, favours White. Black does not have the c5-square for his knight while
the position of the c4-knight is secured. Black's knights lack space which
leads to some coordination problems. White's plan is fairly simple. First of
all, the rook will invade the a-file while the king will reach the d3-square.
Black should also reckon with White's idea of installing a knight on c6.
Afterwards, White can start gaining space on the kingside, further
restricting Black's pieces. When Black's pieces are completely uncoordinated,
White should carry out the advance e4-e5.} 22. f3 {White strengthens the
centre and prevents eventual mating ideas on the first rank. Nevertheless, I
am not convinced that this is the optimal continuation.} ({The straightforward
} 22. g4 {is not convincing enough. After the following forced sequence} f5 23.
Ra7 Nef6 24. g5 Nxe4 25. Rxd7 Nxc3 26. Bd2 Rb1+ 27. Kg2 Nxd5 28. Ne3 Nxe3+ 29.
Bxe3 Kf7 {, the endgame is by no means clear. Black's central pawns can be
really dangerous.}) ({In my opinion, the most precise continuation would be} 
22. h4 $1 {Gaining space on the kingside and creating the h2-square for the
king.} {After} f5 {White can stabilize the position with} 23. exf5 Nef6 24. Ne3
{when Black's compensation for the pawn is problematic.}) 22... f5 23. exf5 Rb3
$2 {This is an obvious mistake since the c3-pawn is not so important. Now,
White has enough time to develop his initiative.} ({More precise would have
been} 23... Nef6 24. Ne3 Nb6 25. Bg5 Kf7 26. fxg6+ hxg6 27. Bxf6 Kxf6 28. Ra7
Rb2 $44) 24. Na5 $1 {As pointed out earlier, in many cases, the knight can
occupy the c6-square.} Rxc3 25. Nc6 {Now, it is already impossible to defend
the e7-pawn.} Nef6 26. Nxe7+ Kf7 27. Bxd6 Rd3 28. fxg6+ hxg6 29. Nc6 ({Another
promising option would have been} 29. Ra7 c4 30. Nc6 Rxd5 31. Bb4 {with a huge
advantage for White.}) 29... Rxd5 30. Nd8+ Ke8 31. Nb7 $16 {White has a
healthy extra pawn. Later on, he managed to convert the advantage, not without
technical difficulties. The remaining part of the game is not related to our
topic and I leave it without comments.} c4 32. Bb4 Nb6 33. Ba5 Nfd7 34. Re1+
Kf8 35. Bb4+ Kg8 36. Re8+ Kf7 37. Re7+ Kg8 38. Re6 g5 39. Nd6 Rd1+ 40. Re1 Rd3
41. Re8+ Kg7 42. Re7+ Kg6 43. Ne4 Nd5 44. Rxd7 Nxb4 45. Rc7 Rd4 46. g4 Rd1+ 47.
Kf2 Rc1 48. h3 Nd3+ 49. Ke2 Nf4+ 50. Kd2 Rh1 51. Rc6+ Kg7 52. Nxg5 c3+ 53. Rxc3
Rh2+ 54. Kd1 Kg6 55. Rc5 Nd3 56. Rf5 Kh6 57. Nf7+ Kg7 58. Ne5 Nb2+ 59. Ke1 Rxh3
60. Rf7+ Kg8 61. Ra7 Rh6 62. f4 Rh4 63. f5 Rh3 64. Ke2 Rh2+ 65. Kf3 Nd1 66. Rd7
Rf2+ 67. Kg3 Rf1 68. f6 Nc3 69. Rd8+ 1-0

