{[#]} {Black has just played 16...Ne8 with the idea of 17...Nc7. As usually
happens in such situations, White immediately starts creating problems on the
other wing. Zubarev played the typical} 17. Bg5 $1 {provoking ...f7-f6 which
is very bad for Black with the dark-squared bishop being on g7.} f6 18. Bd2 ({
Probably, I would have preferred} 18. Be3 {leaving the d2-square available for
the knight.}) 18... Nc7 19. h4 {By leaving the b5-pawn White tries to weaken
the opponent's kingside. Despite the fact that this is a typical idea in such
positions, White could have taken measures to protect the b5-pawn. In the
future, the advance h2-h4-h5 would have been still possible.} ({Better was} 19.
Ra3 $1 Rb8 20. Qc4 {White is ready to answer ...Nxb5 with Rb3. He can already
think of h2-h4-h5. Another idea is to enter the seventh rank by means of Qa2
followed by Ra7. Of course, this idea shall be executed with care because of
the vulnerable b5-pawn.}) 19... h5 $2 {This weakening move is a mistake. Black
should have focused on taking the b5-pawn.} ({Objectively speaking, White
would have kept the advantage in any case. A possible line would be} 19... Rb8
20. h5 Nxb5 21. Qxb5 Qxb5 22. Nxb5 Rxb5 23. Ra7 Nb6 24. Rxe7 Rxb2 25. Re6 Nc4
26. Bf4 $16 {White is better.}) 20. Ra3 $1 {White finds the right idea. Black
will no longer be able to regain the pawn.} Rb8 21. Qc4 Kh7 22. Ra5 {[%cal
Gc4a2] Protecting b5 and preparing Qa2} Nb6 23. Qa2 Ra8 24. b3 $1 {Important
positional move. White takes the c4-square under control. Additionally, in the
future, after the exchange of the rooks, it will be possible to challenge the
b6-knight with Na4.} Rxa5 25. Qxa5 Qb8 26. Na4 {White is already winning.
Black cannot stop the b-pawn.} Nca8 27. Nxb6 Nxb6 28. Qa6 {[%cal Gd2a5] The
bishop is ready to enter the game via a5. The game is over.} c4 29. Be3 c3 30.
Qxb6 Qxb6 31. Bxb6 c2 32. Be3 Bh6 33. Nd4 Bxe3 34. Nxc2 Bc5 35. b4 Ba7 36. Na3
Kg7 37. Nc4 Kf7 38. b6 Bb8 39. Na5 1-0

