{[#]Black has managed to coordinate his pieces. He is already planning to
attack the b5-pawn with the manoeuvre...Ne8-c7. White should play very
energetically. In the game, he decided to break in the centre with} 15. e5 $1 (
{Another possibility would have been to prepare e4-e5 with} 15. Bf4 {In this
case, however, Black can play} Rxa1 16. Rxa1 Qb7 {[%cal Gf6e8,Ge8c7] Stopping
e4-e5 by taking the d5-pawn under control.}) {The following sequence is pretty
logical:} 15... dxe5 16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. Qxe5 Qb7 $6 {This move is not precise
since it allows the break d5-d6.} ({Better would have been} 17... Qd8 {taking
the d6-square under control. Nevertheless, this move does not solve the
problems. White can follow with the calm} 18. h3 {underlining the fact that
Black has run out of counterplay. A possible follow-up would be} Ne8 19. Qe2
Nd6 20. Rxa8 Rxa8 21. Bg5 {when White is a healthy pawn up.}) 18. Rxa8 Rxa8 19.
Re1 Ra7 20. d6 $1 {The break decides the game.} exd6 21. Qxd6 Qc8 22. Bg5 Ne8
23. Qd8 Qxd8 24. Bxd8 $18 {The endgame is hopeless for Black.} Nd6 25. b6 Ra8
26. Bc7 Nb7 27. g4 Bxc3 28. bxc3 Kf8 29. Bf4 f6 30. Re6 Kf7 31. Rc6 Re8 32. Be3
Re6 33. Rc7+ Re7 34. Bxc5 Nxc5 35. Rxc5 Re1+ 36. Kg2 Rb1 37. Rc6 1-0

