{[#] It is clear that in a long-term the b5-pawn
will be lost. Black is planning to follow with the usual ...Nc7. On the other
hand, White's pieces are perfectly arranged to strike in the centre. The
Brazilian grandmaster executes this advance without wasting time.} 17. e5 $1 {
This break could have been carried out also after the prior exchange of the
rooks. The critical position arises after the following sequence} Nxe5 18. Nxe5
dxe5 19. Bxe5 Bxe5 20. Qxe5 Rxa1 21. Rxa1 Nd6 {It transpires that Black will
eliminate the b5-pawn and the knights will be exchanged. Of course, White can
take the e7-pawn. In the arising endgame, White will be better due to his
advanced central passer and the vulnerable black king.} 22. Rc1 $2 {White is
going for the wrong pawn. As mentioned above, it was more important to focus
on the e-pawn.} ({Better was} 22. Re1 $1 {forcing the transition into the
following endgame:} Nxb5 23. Nxb5 Qxb5 24. Qxe7 Qxb2 25. d6 Qd4 26. d7 Kg7 {
I will analyze this position in detail because of two main reasons: 1) heavy
piece endgames with a central passed pawn on d7 arises very often in practice
2) exactly the same endgame configuration is very likely to arise in Benko
when White leaves the queenside and goes for e4-e5. Generally speaking, when
evaluating endgames with heavy pieces, the safety of the king is the most
important factor that we take into consideration. As it will become clear from
the following analysis, the black king is much more vulnerable in this
position. White's passed pawn is more advanced and engages Black's pieces.
Therefore, White has the advantage in this endgame. It is important to point
out that White cannot win only by using the passed pawn. The tactical ideas
related to the promotion of the pawn should be combined with threats against
the black king. Additionally, White should always pay attention to the c-pawn
which is Black's main source of counterplay.} 27. Rf1 {White puts the rook on
a safe square and prepares Qe8.} c4 28. Qe8 Qb6 {This is the most tenacious
defence. Black keeps the option of playing ...Qd8 at some point.} ({After} 
28... Qd6 {White has the typical} 29. Qc8 $1 {freeing the e8-square for the
rook and keeping the c4-pawn under control. Black is in some kind of a
zugzwang.} g5 30. h3 h5 31. Re1 {Black should already reckon with the idea
Qxb8 followed by Re8.} h4 32. Kh1 $1 {A very strong prophylactic move. By
removing the king from the diagonal a7-g1, White prepares f2-f4. As mentioned
earlier, it is essential to create threats on the kingside.} ({The immediate} 
32. Qxb8 $2 {leads to perpetual after} Qxb8 33. Re8 Qb1+ 34. Kh2 Qf5 35. d8=Q
Qf4+ $11) 32... Kh7 33. f4 $1 g4 {Only move.} ({After} 33... gxf4 $2 {the idea}
34. Qxb8 Qxb8 35. Re8 {is already working since there is no perpetual.}) 34.
Qe8 Kg7 ({The alternative} 34... Qxf4 {does not help either. After} 35. hxg4 h3
36. d8=Q hxg2+ 37. Kg1 $18 {White is winning.}) 35. f5 gxh3 36. f6+ $1 {
Finally. White manages to put Black's king in danger.} Kg6 37. Qe4+ Kxf6 38.
Qf3+ Kg7 39. Rd1 Qe7 40. gxh3 $18 {with a mating attack.}) 29. Qe5+ Kg8 ({
The alternative is} 29... f6 {when the position is getting really sharp.} 30.
Qe7+ Kh6 31. Rd1 Rd8 32. h4 $1 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] A key idea. White is
threatening g2-g4-g5. After} c3 33. g4 c2 34. g5+ {Black faces a choice. The
most precise defence would be} fxg5 ({The alternative} 34... Kh5 $2 {is losing
due to} 35. Qe2+ Kxh4 36. Qxc2 Qb4 (36... Kxg5 37. Qd2+ Kh5 38. Kg2 $18) 37.
Qd3 Qg4+ 38. Kf1 Kxg5 39. Qe3+ Kh5 40. Rd4 Qf5 41. Qe7 $18) 35. hxg5+ Kh5 36.
Qe2+ Kxg5 37. Qxc2 $14 {White keeps an advantage due to the far-advanced pawn
and the Black's vulnerable king,}) 30. Re1 {[%cal Ge5b8,Ge1e8]} Rd8 31. Qe8+
Kg7 32. h4 $1 {By freeing the h2-square for the king, White prepares 33.Re7.}
c3 33. Re7 Qf6 34. Qxd8 c2 35. Rxf7+ Qxf7 36. Qc8 c1=Q+ 37. Qxc1 Qxd7 $14 {
Objectively speaking, Black should be able to hold this position. White,
however, keeps winning chances.}) 22... Nxb5 23. Nxb5 Qxb5 24. Rxc5 {This was
the point of White's previous play. Black, however, has an important resource
at his disposal:} Ra8 $1 {Probably White missed this strong intermediate move.}
25. Rc1 e6 26. b4 exd5 $6 {Not the most precise way to make a draw.} ({Better
would have been} 26... Rd8 {with an immediate draw.}) 27. Qd4 {The position is
equal but White's play remains easier because of his outside passed pawn and
the somewhat vulnerable black king.} h5 28. h4 Rd8 29. f3 Qe2 30. Kh2 Qe6 $6 {
Another inaccuracy. It is not desirable to allow b4-b5.} ({The normal
continuation would be} 30... Qb5 $11) 31. b5 Qd6+ 32. Kg1 Rb8 33. Rc5 Kh7 $4 {
This is the decisive mistake. Black gives the pawn for free.} ({The simple} 
33... Rd8 {maintains the balance.}) 34. Rxd5 Qe6 35. Kh2 Rb7 36. Rd8 f6 37. Rd6
Qe5+ 38. Qxe5 fxe5 39. b6 Kg7 1-0

