{THE CONSTRUCTION NB5 - A4 - B3  This construction is White's most classical
approach to restrict Black's queenside play. The dream position for White
arises when the only remaining minor pieces are the b5-knight and Black's
dark-squared bishop. If in such position White has prevented the idea ...c5-c4,
then Black is strategically lost.  Since the queenside is locked, White can
start playing in the centre by means of f2-f4 and e4-e5. On the diagram
position, White can apply exactly the same strategy. Playing in the centre is
the best plan in positions with queens on the board. While looking at the
diagram, let's imagine that the queens, as well as a pair of rooks, have been
exchanged. In this case, after securing the b3-pawn, White will execute the
manoeuvre Na3-c4 followed by a4-a5. The next step would be to bring the rook
into play by means of b3-b4.  All these scenarios, as well as other important
typical ideas, are presented in the model games that follow.}  *

