{ [#] Black wants to remove the b5-bishop and make the b-file available
for his rooks. Therefore, he is planning to proceed with ...Nc7.  At this
point, Turov has taken a very good positional decision:} 21. Bxa6 $1 Qxa6 22.
Nb5 {This is an important typical position that you should remember. In
positions with a knight against a dark-squared bishop, White tries to achieve
the construction a4, b3, and Nb5. Since there are no black knights on the
board, the b5-knight can never be exchanged. Black has no counterplay and
should act according to White's ideas. Having blocked the queenside, White
should start playing on the other wing. He has plenty of time to prepare this
plan.} Bg7 23. f4 {White starts playing in the centre and on the kingside.
Black should already reckon with the idea e4-e5. In the next moves, White
slowly prepares his kingside play.} Qb7 24. Rfe1 Bh6 25. g3 Rad8 26. Kh2 Rd7
27. Qc4 Ra8 28. Rcd1 Bf8 29. Re2 Rad8 {White have put his pieces on their
ideal squares. Now, it's already time for concrete actions. For the moment,
Black is well prepared against the advance e4-e5. White, however, has another
resource at his disposal. He went for} 30. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5] This is the
right way to go about the position. Before playing e4-e5, White is trying to
further weaken Black's kingside with h4-h5 followed by hxg6.} Bg7 31. h5 Re8 $2
{Mistake in a very difficult position. With his last move, Black releases the
pressure on d5. Therefore, White needs no preparation to execute the advance
e4-e5.} 32. hxg6 hxg6 33. e5 $1 {This is the point. Black's position is
already lost.} dxe5 34. fxe5 Red8 35. d6 $6 {White shouldn't have rushed with
this advance. Now, Black gets at least some play.} ({More to the point was} 35.
Qe4 {preparing to further weaken the black king with e5-e6.}) 35... e6 $2 {
It is impossible to live with the strong protected passed pawn on d6.} ({
Better was} 35... exd6 {Even in this case, however, after} 36. Nxd6 Qb4 37.
Qxb4 cxb4 38. Rdd2 $18 {White is technically winning.}) 36. Qe4 {White is in 
full control. The rest is easy.} Qb6 37. Kg2 Rc8 38. Rc1 Rdd8 39. Rc4 Bh6 40.
Rec2 Qa5 41. Rf2 Bg7 42. Qb7 Rf8 43. Rcf4 Rb8 44. Qf3 Bxe5 45. Rxf7 Bg7 46. d7
Qb6 47. Na7 Rxf7 48. Qxf7+ Kh7 49. Kf1 Qa6+ 50. Nb5 1-0

