{[#] Black is trying to remove the queenside blockade and White should decide
whether to exchange the knights or not. In the game, he took the right
decision:} 22. Na3 $1 {In Benko structures (and in positions with a space
advantage in general), it is desirable to refrain from exchanging pieces. In
this case, many opponent pieces will be fighting for very few squares.
Additionally, with his last move, White is taking under control the important
c4-square, making difficult for Black to execute the typical ...c5-c4 advance.}
Qa6 23. Qxa6 {Exchanging the queens is not an easy decision since White will
no longer be able to create real threats on the kingside. After this exchange,
White must win on the queenside.} ({I would have preferred} 23. Nc4 {leaving
open the possibility to play on both wings. White can consider not only the
typical e4-e5 but also ideas like Qe3 followed by Bh6 and h2-h4.}) 23... Nxa6
24. Nb5 {Once again, White establishes his typical queenside blockade. Also,
under favourable circumstances, he can make use of the c6-square since the
manoeuvre Na7-c6 is possible.} Nb4 ({The attempt to remove the blockade with} 
24... Nc7 $2 {does not work due to} 25. Na7 Re8 26. Nc6 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4]
with total domination. White is ready to transfer the other knight to c4.})
25. Bd2 Nd3 26. Rc2 Nf6 ({At any point, you should check if the typical} 26...
c4 {is working or not. In this position, White can play} 27. Rxc4 Rxc4 28. bxc4
Ra8 29. a5 Nb2 30. Nfd4 Nxc4 31. Be1 $18 {with a healthy extra pawn.}) 27. Ne1
Nxe1 28. Rxe1 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gc5c4,Ge5d3] The knight is heading to e5 in
order to prepare the advance ...c5-c4 or to occupy the d3-square.} ({Another
option would be} 28... Ne8 {[%cal Ge8c7] with the thematic idea to exchange
the b5-knight via c7. White has many ways to play the position, but the most
accurate seems to be} 29. g4 $1 {This is a useful move in such structures.
White grabs space on the kingside and makes difficult for Black to carry out
the advance ...f7-f5.} Nc7 ({Black can prepare the move ...Nc7 by taking the
a7-square under control with} 29... Rb7 {Even the exchange of the knights,
however, does not create problems for White. For example, after} 30. Kf1 Nc7
31. Nxc7 Rcxc7 32. Rb1 {[%cal Ga4a5] Black has no time to create queenside
pressure while the a-pawn is already very dangerous.}) 30. Na7 Re8 31. Ba5 $1 {
A concrete approach to the position which works quite well here.} Na6 ({
The alternative} 31... Rb7 {is well met by} 32. Bxc7 $1 Rxa7 ({After} 32...
Rxc7 33. Nb5 $18 {we achieve a type of position which was already discussed.
White has the construction Nb5, b3, a4, while the only remaining black minor
piece is the dark-squared bishop. In such cases, Black has no queenside
counterplay. White can already start expanding in the centre and on the
kingside.}) 33. Bb6 Raa8 34. a5 $18 {White is winning. He can bring the king
all the way to b5 and open the queenside with b3-b4.}) 32. Nb5 {[%cal Gf2f4,
Ge4e5] Once again, White managed to block the queenside. He can now consider
playing in the centre by means of f2-f4 followed by e4-e5.}) 29. Rb1 Ra8 30. f3
Ne5 ({Again, White should reckon with} 30... c4 $6 {This time, the most
convincing reaction seems to be} 31. Na3 $1 {when Black has several
possibilities.} Nb6 {This move seems the most tenacious try.} ({After} 31...
cxb3 32. Rxc8+ Rxc8 33. Rxb3 {White enjoys a healthy extra pawn.}) ({In a case
of} 31... c3 {White can just follow with} 32. Be3 {[%cal Ga3b5,Gb1c1]
Preparing Nb5 and Rbc1.}) {The game might continue} 32. Be3 cxb3 33. Rxc8+ Nxc8
34. Rxb3 Ke8 35. Rb4 Bc3 36. Rc4 Ba5 37. Kf2 Kd7 38. Nb5 $16 {Black does not
have enough compensation for the pawn.}) 31. Kf1 Ke8 32. Ke2 f5 (32... c4 $2 {
runs into} 33. f4 $1 $18) 33. Na3 {Since everything is under control, the
knight can leave the b-file.} fxe4 34. fxe4 Rcb8 35. a5 Nd7 36. Nc4 {This
position requires some clarifications. In the middlegame, when the queens are
on the board, White keeps the construction Nb5, b3, a4. In the endgame (with
queens being exchanged), when the b3-pawn is well protected, White can switch
to another thematic construction - Nc4, a5, b3. The a5-pawn paralyzes Black's
pieces and White shall already start playing on the queenside with b3-b4.} Rb5
37. b4 cxb4 38. Rxb4 Rxb4 39. Bxb4 $18 {White is winning since Black does not
have compensation for the pawn. I leave the remaining part of the game without
comments.} Bd4 40. Ra2 Ra6 41. Kd3 Ba7 42. h3 Kd8 43. Rb2 Bg1 44. Re2 Bc5 45.
Bc3 e6 46. dxe6 Nf8 47. Bf6+ Ke8 48. e7 Ne6 49. Rb2 Ba7 50. Rb6 Rxb6 51. axb6
Bb8 52. Ne3 Nc5+ 53. Kd4 Nd7 54. Nd5 Nxb6 55. Nxb6 Ba7 56. Kd5 Bxb6 57. Kxd6
Bf2 58. Ke6 Bc5 59. Bg5 Bb4 60. h4 Bc3 61. e5 Be1 62. Kf6 h6 63. Bxh6 Bxh4+ 64.
Kxg6 Bg3 65. Kf5 Kxe7 66. Bf4 1-0

