{[#] White has achieved a
dream position. The queenside is locked and he can now start playing in the
centre.} 21. f4 $1 {[%cal Gh1e1,Ge4e5] This is the right way to go about the
position. White is planning to prepare the advance e4-e5 by means of Rhe1.}
Nxc4 22. Qxc4 Rb6 23. Rhe1 Rb7 24. Rd3 {[%cal Gd3e3,Ge4e5] Played with the
idea Rde3 followed by e4-e5. Black is helpless.} Re8 25. Kh1 $1 {An important
prophylactic move. Of course, before executing the central break, it is
desirable to remove the king from the opposition along the b8-h2 diagonal.} h5
26. Rde3 Bh6 27. e5 {Finally, White breaks in the centre. Black's position is
collapsing.} dxe5 28. Rxe5 Bg7 29. R5e4 Rd7 30. d6 $1 {This final break is
decisive. White is winning.} Rxd6 31. Nxd6 Qxd6 32. Rc1 Rb8 33. Qxc5 Qxc5 34.
Rxc5 Rxb3 35. Rc8+ Bf8 36. Rd4 e5 37. Rdd8 exf4 38. Rxf8+ 1-0

