{[#] We have a very typical Benko position. Since the b5-knight is going to be
exchanged by means of ...Nc7, White shall find an alternative to the classical
queenside construction Nb5, a4, b3. Such an alternative would be Nc4, a4, b3.
Being on c4, the knight supports the play in the centre and also prevents
Black from executing the typical ...c5-c4 advance. Since the b-file will
remain available for Black, White shall make sure that the b3-pawn would be
safely covered. In the game, Kotanjian played} 14. Ra3 $1 {The idea of this
subtle move is to prepare b2-b3 bu sidestepping the opposition on the long
diagonal.} Nc7 15. Nxc7 Qxc7 16. Qc2 {[%cal Gd2c4,Gb2b4] After having the
e4-pawn protected, White is ready to proceed with Nc4. Meanwhile, the last
move threatens b2-b4, creating two connected passed pawns on the queenside.}
Ra7 17. Nc4 Nd7 18. Bd2 $1 {In such positions, d2 is the perfect spot for the
bishop. The bishop covers the b4-square and supports the advance a4-a5. In the
endgame, after playing a4-a5, White will try to open the queenside by means of
b2-b4.} Ne5 19. b3 {The idea behind 14.Ra3 becomes clear. Black's counterplay
is far from obvious.} Rb8 20. Rb1 Qb7 21. a5 {A typical move in such positions.
After safely protecting the b3-pawn, White starts expanding on the queenside.
With his last move, he prepares Ra4, thus increasing the control of the
c4-square and supporting b3-b4.} ({Nevertheless, in this position White has
a simpler solution:} 21. Nxe5 Bxe5 22. b4 cxb4 23. Rxb4 Qc8 24. Rxb8 Qxb8 25. Rb3
{with a winning position.}) 21... Qa6 22. Ra4 Rab7 23. Nb6 {Black's queenside
counterplay is completely restricted. White can already consider playing b3-b4.
} Nd7 24. Nxd7 Rxd7 25. Qc4 $1 {After the exchange of the queens, White is
winning by executing the advance b3-b4. We can now see the advantages of 22.
Ra4.} Qxc4 26. Rxc4 Rdb7 27. b4 $2 {In this position, the generally desirable
b3-b4 does not work tactically.} ({When the pawn is on a5 and the queen is
exchanged, White can apply another typical device - sacrifice the b3-pawn and
support the advance of the a-pawn. In this line of thoughts, a logical
continuation would be} 27. Kf1 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gf1e2,Ge2d1,Gd1c2] with the
idea of bringing the king all the way to c2. The point can be seen after} Rxb3
28. Rxb3 Rxb3 29. Ra4 $1 Rb8 30. a6 Ra8 31. Ke2 {[%cal Ge2d3,Gd3c4,Gc4b5]
White is winning. The king is heading to b5. I will demonstrate the winning
line, just to make sure that you will be confident when entering such a
position.} Kf8 32. Kd3 Ke8 33. Kc4 Kd7 34. Kb5 Bd4 35. a7 Bxf2 36. Ka6 c4 37.
Kb7 $18) 27... h5 $2 {Black misses his chance.} ({Necessary was} 27... Rb5 $1 {
[%cal Gb5a5] with the idea ...Rxa5. It turns out that White cannot hold the
pawns. A possible follow-up would be} 28. a6 Ra8 29. Rbc1 Bb2 30. R1c2 Ba3 31.
bxc5 Bxc5 32. Ra4 Rb6 33. h4 Rbxa6 34. Rxa6 Rxa6 $11) 28. Kf1 Rb5 {Now, it is
too late since White just plays} 29. Ke2 e6 ({Impossible is} 29... Rxa5 {due to
} 30. bxa5 Rxb1 31. Ra4 $18) 30. Rb3 {Getting ready for Ra3 in the suitable
moment.} exd5 31. exd5 Kh7 32. a6 Ra8 33. Ra3 Rb6 34. bxc5 dxc5 35. a7 Rb7 36.
Rca4 $18 {White is already winning. The rest is simple.} Rd7 37. Be3 Bf8 38.
Ra6 Rxd5 39. Rb3 Bd6 40. Rd3 Rxd3 41. Kxd3 Bxh2 42. g3 f5 43. Kc4 Kg8 1-0

