{[#] Usually, when White cannot hold the blockade on b5, he is trying to
transfer his other knight to c4. Being on c4, the knight prevents the advance .
..c5-c4 and supports the play in the centre. Additionally, when the knight is
on c4, White usually plays a4-a5 (this is difficult when the knight is on b5).
The game followed} 14. Nd2 Nc7 15. Nc4 Qb7 16. Nxc7 Qxc7 17. Bg5 {A typical
idea in Benko structures. The indirect pressure on e7, Makes difficult for
Black to execute the manoeuvre Nd7-e5 (b6), thus challenging the c4-knight.} ({
On the other hand, when having the construction Nc4, a4, I prefer} 17. Bd2 {
covering the b4-square and supporting the advances a4-a5 and b2-b4.} {The
thematic} Nd7 18. a5 Ne5 {does not work in view of} 19. Nb6 $1 Ra7 20. b4 {
White is winning. One of the nice lines would be} Nd3 21. Qxd3 Bxa1 22. Rxa1
Qxb6 23. Bc3 Qb7 24. b5 $18) 17... Rfb8 18. a5 Kf8 {[%cal Gf6d7] Black insists
on the move ...Nd7. Otherwise, it wouldn't be possible to make the bishop work.
} 19. Ra4 {[%cal Gf1a1] White is putting his two cents on the a-pawn. With his
last move, he covers the b4-square and prepares 20.Rfa1.} ({It also
possible to start playing in the centre with} 19. f4) 19... Nd7 20. Rfa1 Ra7 {
Black prepares 20...Ne5, sidestepping 21.Nb6. This move, however, gives White
an additional possibility.} ({The immediate} 20... Ne5 {is well met by} 21. Nb6
Ra7 22. Bd2 $1 {As pointed out earlier, in such positions, the bishop belongs
to d2.} Nd7 23. h4 $1 {Freeing the h2-square for the king and preparing to
weaken the black king by means of h4-h5.} h5 24. Nxd7+ Qxd7 25. Bc3 {After the
exchange of the bishops, White's advantage would be almost decisive. Generally
speaking, the endgames with heavy pieces are good for Black, but this position
is an exception. The far advanced a-pawn ties up Black's pieces. In the
appropriate moment, White will start creating threats against the black king.})
21. Bf4 $1 {This move rules out any ...Ne5 ideas. Black has run out of
counterplay.} Qb7 22. h3 Qb5 23. Qc2 Ne5 24. Bxe5 Bxe5 25. a6 {White prefers
not to part with his strong knight.} ({Of course,} 25. Nxe5 dxe5 26. R1a2 $18 {
is hopeless for Black.}) 25... Bd4 26. Ra5 Qd7 27. R1a3 e6 28. Rb3 $1 {Trying
to exchange Black's only active piece.} Re8 {[%cal Ge6d5,Ge8e1] Opening the
e-file and invading White's camp is Black's last hope. Brodsky, however, opted
for the precise} 29. Ra1 $1 {covering the first rank. The rest is simple} exd5
30. exd5 Qd8 31. Rb7 Re7 32. Rb6 Red7 33. Rc6 Kg7 34. Qd2 Qf6 35. Re1 Qf5 36.
Nxd6 Qxd5 37. Ne8+ Kf8 38. Qh6+ 1-0

