{[#] It seems that Black has achieved a lot. He has blocked the a2-pawn (White
cannot play a2-a4 followed by Nb5) while the g7-bishop is without an opponent.
Black is now threatening the thematic ...c5-c4. Nevertheless, White has a
strong manoeuvre at his disposal:} 21. Nd1 $1 {[%cal Gd1e3,Ge3c4] The knight is
heading to the c4-square.After chasing the queen away, he would play a2-a4,
thus building his desired construction.} Rb7 22. Ne3 Rba7 23. Qd3 Qb4 24. a4 {
After this key move, the activity of black rooks is seriously restricted.} Rb8
{[%cal Ga7a4] Black is threatening 25...Rxa4. Therefore, White decided to
chase the queen away with} 25. Nc2 Qa5 26. Na3 $1 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Ga3b5] A
smart idea. White is planning to install his knights on c4 and b5. Meanwhile,
he discourages any ...c5-c4 related ideas.} Rb4 27. Rc1 ({The immediate} 27.
Nd2 {was also possible.}) 27... Ra8 28. Nd2 Rab8 29. Ndc4 Ne5 30. Nxa5 ({
The generally desirable} 30. Nxe5 $2 {runs into the intermediate} Rxb3 $1 {
when the position is equal.}) 30... Nxd3 31. Rb1 {[%cal Ga5c6] Black must
already reckon with the idea of Nc6.} Ra8 32. Nc6 Rb7 33. Rc2 {White had many
good moves in this position because Black's counterplay is limited. With his
last move, Banusz anticipates the appearance of the black rook on b4 after the
prior exchange of the knights. Indeed, the game followed} Nb4 34. Nxb4 Rxb4 35.
Rc4 {This was the point behind 33.Rc2. The queenside is now blocked and Black
has no counterplay at all.} Rab8 ({White was probably planning to answer} 35...
Rb7 {with} 36. Nb5 {[%cal Gf2f4] followed by a central play.}) 36. Rxb4 Rxb4
37. Nc4 {Once again, we see this perfect for White endgame - knight
against a dark-squared bishop. Black has no play and should only observe how
White gradually realizes his plan.} Kf8 38. Kf3 {[%cal Gf3e2,Ge2d3] The king
is going to d3. Afterwards, White will decide whether to go a4-a5 or Na5-c6.}
Ke8 39. Ke2 Kd7 40. Kd3 f5 41. f3 fxe4+ 42. fxe4 Rb8 43. Na5 $1 {This move is
now possible because Black does not have ...Rd4.} Rb4 ({The alternative} 43...
Rf8 {does not help either. For example:} 44. Nc6 Rf3+ 45. Kc4 Rxg3 46. a5 Kc7
47. b4 cxb4 48. Kxb4 Rxh3 49. a6 $18 {White is winning.}) 44. Nc6 c4+ 45. Kc2 {
Black wins the a4-pawn, Black the white rook invades the b7-square.} cxb3+ 46.
Rxb3 Rxe4 ({White is also winning after} 46... Rxa4 47. Rb7+ Kc8 48. Rxe7 $18)
47. Rb7+ Ke8 48. a5 $18 {The a-pawn is unstoppable. White is winning.} Rc4+ 49.
Kb3 Rc3+ 50. Kb4 Rc1 51. a6 Rb1+ 52. Kc4 Rc1+ 53. Kd3 Rd1+ 54. Kc2 Ra1 55. a7
Kf7 56. Rxe7+ Kf6 57. Re8 1-0

