{THE ADVANCE B2(B3) - B4 The advance b2(b3) - b4 is another typical device in
Benko structures. This idea has two main purposes: 1) create two connected
passed pawns if Black is unable to answer with ...cxb4 2) make possible the
manoeuvre Nd4-c6 after deflecting the c5-pawn Before opting for this advance,
White should pay attention to some possible dangers. Sometimes, after ...cxb4,
the activity of Black's pieces provides more than enough compensation for the
extra pawn. It is important to point out, that the black knight gets the
active c4-square. Another problem could arise if Black manages to quickly
follow with c5-c4-c3 (especially in positions with many pieces on the board).
In such a situation, Black's advanced c-pawn might be even more important than
White's two pawns. On the diagram, you see a typical case in which the advance
b3-b4 is working well. Since Black cannot take on b4 (due to the opposition of
the queens), White can start advancing his connected passed pawns. In the
model games, you will see many typical situations connected with the advance
b2(b3)-b4.}  *

