{[#] Black has just played 13...Nc7 with the idea to remove the queenside
blockade. White opted a typical motif you should be familiar with:} 14. Nxc7
Qxc7 15. b4 $1 {By using the opposition along the c-file, White seizes the
chance to create two passed pawns on the queenside.} Nd7 16. Ra2 Rfc8 {Black
rightly tries to build his counterplay by further advancing the c-pawn.} 17. b5
c4 18. Bc3 {Even though this move is also winning, it is preferable to avoid
Black's blockade on a5 and b6. In some positions, when White is not so well
coordinated, Black puts queen on a6 and knight on b6. Later on, he starts
pushing the c-pawn. In some cases, even White is the one who struggles to
equalize. In the current game, Black tries to apply exactly the same approach.
This time, however, the concept is not working tactically.} ({Better was} 18.
a5 c3 19. b6 Qb7 20. Be3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gd4c6] followed by Nd4-c6 with a winning
position.}) 18... Bxc3 19. Qxc3 Qa5 20. Rc1 Nb6 21. Qc2 $1 {[%csl Gf3][%cal
Gf3d4,Gd4c6] White is preparing Nd4-c6 while the a4-pawn is defended
tactically. Generally speaking, if Black gets ...c4-c3 followed by ...Rc4 and .
..Rac8, he is doing very well. In this case, however, it is impossible.} Nxa4 (
21... c3 {[%cal Gc8c4] runs into} 22. Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4c6]}) 22. Rca1 c3 23. b6
$1 {This is the point. The b-pawn spoils Black's coordination.} Qxb6 24. Rxa4
Rxa4 25. Rxa4 {Being a piece up White is completely winning.} Qb2 26. Ne1 f6
27. Kf1 Qb5+ 28. Nd3 Kf7 29. Rb4 Qa5 30. g3 Qa1+ 31. Kg2 Qa5 32. Rb3 Qa4 33.
Nb4 Kg7 34. Rxc3 1-0

