{[#] In this position, Black's idea is to enter an endgame with heavy pieces
after exchanging the knights via c7-square. In Benko structures, Black is
doing well in endgames with only heavy pieces remaining on the board. The
reason is simple. When the minor pieces are already exchanged, White's space
advantage is not significant. Black's rooks and queen are working on the
semi-open "a" and "b" files while white major pieces are staring at the white
pawns (and the c5-pawn). This difference in the activity of the heavy pieces
provides Black with enough compensation for the pawn. White decided to change
the structure by playing} 22. b4 {Exchanging the c5-pawn is not one-sided.
Besides his passed a-pawn, White also gets the d4-square (the manoeuvre Nd4-c6
becomes possible). On the other hand, opening the queenside gives Black's
pieces some activity. For example, the c5-square is a perfect spot for the
black knight. In the previous examples, we have seen that in many cases, Black
even manages to win the a4-pawn. This position requires a very precise play.} (
{Objectively speaking, stronger would have been} 22. b3 Rfb8 23. h3 Ne8 24.
Rfb1 Rb7 {[%cal Ge8c7]} ({The immdiate} 24... Nc7 {allows the thematic} 25.
Nxc7 Qxc7 26. b4 $1 {[%csl Rc7] creating two connected passed pawns on the
queenside.}) 25. Na3 $1 Nc7 26. Nc4 {It turns out that Black cannot increase
his queenside pressure. For example, the knight transfer to b4 does not change
anything. Meanwhile, White will start playing in the centre by means of f3-f4
followed by e4-e5.}) 22... Nd7 {The knight is getting ready to occupy the key
c5-square. The next few moves are quite logical.} 23. Rfb1 Rfb8 24. h3 cxb4 25.
Qxb4 Nc5 26. Qd4 Nd7 $2 {This is the decisive mistake. Black shouldn't have
exchanged the queens since the a-pawn is getting very dangerous.} ({Better was
} 26... Ra5 {[%cal Gb8a8]} 27. Nc3 Qd8 28. Rxb8 Qxb8 29. Rb1 Qc7 {when White
still needs to find a way to convert his advantage.}) 27. Qxb6 Rxb6 28. a5 Rbb8
29. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c6] The knight is heading to c6.} ({Even better was} 29. a6 {
[%cal Ga6a7] with the idea a6-a7.}) 29... Rxb1+ 30. Rxb1 Nc5 31. Nc6 $18 {
White has an extra pawn and more active pieces. The position is completely
winning.} Kg7 32. Rb8 Ra6 33. Rb6 Ra8 34. Nxe7 Rxa5 35. Rxd6 Nd3 36. Rb6 Ra1+
37. Kh2 Ra2 38. d6 Ne5 39. Rb5 Nxf3+ 40. Kg3 Nd4 41. d7 Ne6 42. Nc6 Ra8 43. Re5
Nd8 44. Nxd8 Rxd8 45. Rd5 Kf6 46. Kf4 Ke6 47. Kg5 h5 48. h4 Ke7 49. Rd1 Ke6 50.
g3 Ke7 51. Rd2 Ke6 52. Rd3 Ke7 53. Rd5 Ke6 54. Rd1 Ke7 55. Rd2 Ke6 56. Rd3 Ke7
57. Rd4 Ke6 58. Rd5 Ke7 59. Re5+ Kf8 60. Re8+ Rxe8 61. dxe8=Q+ Kxe8 62. Kf6 Kf8
63. e5 Kg8 64. e6 fxe6 65. Kxg6 e5 66. Kxh5 Kf7 67. Kg4 1-0

