{[#]Very often, in Benko structures, Black is exchanging his powerful
dark-squared bishop for the c3-knight in order to regain the pawn. Afterwards,
Black's heavy pieces will be ready to invade the queenside. In such cases,
White should immediately start active actions in the cen ter and on the
kingside.  A similar situation arised in the game Bukavisin - Zablotsky. White
played} {A subtle move. By attacking the e7-pawn, White is trying to provoke
the advance ...f7-f6 which weakens Black's structure. Of course, Black can
play 20...Nf6 or 20...Bf6, but these moves leave the b5-pawn alive.} 20. Bg5 $1
Bxc3 21. bxc3 f6 ({After} 21... Nxb5 {,besides taking on e7, White can also
insert} 22. Nxb5 Bxb5 23. c4 {[%csl Re7] winning a pawn under perfect
circumstances.}) 22. Bh4 Nxb5 23. Nc4 $1 {Of course! In positions with a space
advantage, we should avoid exchanges. From c4, the knight not only prevents
ideas based on ...Rb2, but also supports the central break e4-e5.} Qc7 24. f4 {
[%cal Ge4e5] White starts playing in the center. He already planning to break
with e4-e5. Black has no satisfactory defence.} Ra7 25. e5 $1 {After this
energetic move, Black's position is collapsing.} Rca8 26. Rxa7 Qxa7 27. e6 $1 {
Very good positional decision. The e6-pawn separates the board and prevents
Black's queenside pieces from participating in the defence. White is ready to
follow with f4-f5.} Bc8 28. f5 {After this move, Black is losing on the spot.}
gxf5 $2 ({More tenacious would have been} 28... Qa2 29. Nb2 Nxc3 30. Bc4 Ne4 $1
{This is the only way to remain in the game.} ({After} 30... Qa3 31. fxg6 hxg6
32. Qh6 Ng7 33. Qxg6 {White's attack is decisive. For example:} Ba6 ({Taking
the knight with} 33... Qxb2 {leads to a mate by force:} 34. Qf7+ Kh8 35. Qf8+
Kh7 36. Bd3+ f5 37. Bxf5+ Nxf5 38. Qxf5+ {with mate to follow.}) 34. Be1 $1 $18
{This is a key idea. White closes the first rans and prepares a rook-lift.}
Qxb2 35. Bxa6 Rxa6 36. Qf7+ Kh7 37. Rf3 $18) 31. Qc2 Qa3 32. fxg6 Ba6 33. Bxa6
Qxa6 34. gxh7+ Kh8 35. Re1 $16) 29. Ne3 f4 30. Nf5 c4 31. Qxf4 Nxc3 32. Qg3+
1-0

