[SourceVersionDate "2020.02.06"]

1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 {This system is getting very
popular recently. It has been employed by a number of top-level players,
including Aronian and Ivanchuk. The main point behind White's 5th move is to
slow down Black's queenside counterplay. By immediately bringing the f1-bishop
into the game, White is trying to hold the important b5-square. Later on,
White will reinforce the control of b5 by means of Nc3 and a2-a4. As a result,
with the b-file been blocked, Black's queenside counterplay will be highly
restricted. If Black goes for a classical Benko structure, (...g7-g6, ...Bg7, .
..d7-d6, ...0-0, and ...axb5) the control of the b5-square will be very
important (see the section on the pawn structures).  Of course, We should be
aware of some drawbacks of the move 5.e3. This move does not contribute to the
fight for the centre. Additionally, White would eventually lose a tempo since
in most of the lines he will play e3-e4 at some point. Taking these drawbacks
into account, Black often opts for dynamic systems which are characterized by
the pressure on d5.  Nevertheless, my analysis shows that Black cannot solve
his problems with dynamic play. In many lines, White gives his pawn back in
order to overtake the initiative. When studying openings, we start with the
lines in which the opponent tries to refute our concept. Therefore, I decided
to give priority to Black's dynamic systems.  Chapter 1 starts dealing with
Black's most popular dynamic system.} axb5 6. Bxb5 Qa5+ {This is the most
popular move. Black tries to prove that the b5-bishop is unstable. Of course,
we shall deal with the alternatives to 6...Qa5.} ({It is important to point
out that many transpositions are possible in this line. For example,} 6... Bb7
7. Nc3 Qa5 ({After} 7... e6 8. e4 Qa5 9. Nge2 Nxe4 10. O-O {we have another
transposition to Chapter 2.}) {transposes} 8. Bd2 {transposes to Chapter 2
which deals with the system 6...Qa5 7.Nc3 Bb7.}) ({An independent option is} 
6... Ba6 {which leads to the classical Benko structure.} 7. Bxa6 Nxa6 {This
most natural recapture. Black keeps developing his pieces. Later on, the knight
can go to c7 or b5, thus putting pressure on d5.} ({The move} 7... Qa5+ {
is not independent since after} 8. Nc3 Qxa6 {we have transposition to the line
6...Qa5 7.Nc3 Ba6} ({Another transposition to the same line arises after} 8...
Nxa6)) ({I have also examined} 7... Rxa6 {which is less challenging. White
usually manages to build his typical queenside blockade. The critical position
is being reached after} 8. Nc3 g6 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11. e4 d6 12. Qe2 {
At this point, Black faces a choice. White's concept, however, remains almost
unchanged.} Qb6 {This is the most popular and logical continuation. Besides
putting pressure on the queenside, Black is planning to complete the
development by means of ...Nbd7. The queen, however, is now exposed to the
typical manoeuvre Nd2-c4.} ({The creative} 12... Nfd7 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Gd7b6,
Gb6a4] ,planning ...Nb6-a4 is not sufficient. White is just in time to
perfectly coordinate his pieces. The most straightforward continuation is} 13.
Bf4 {[%cal Ge4e5] Planning e4-e5.} Nb6 14. Rad1 Na4 15. Nxa4 Rxa4 16. b3 Rb4 {
By keeping the rook on the 4th rank, Black is trying to prevent the break
e4-e5.} ({After} 16... Ra8 17. e5 $16 {White has a big advantage.}) 17. Nd2 $1
{The knight is heading to c4. In the Pawn Structures section, you can find
many examples on the construction Nc4 - b3.} Nd7 18. Nc4 $16 {White enjoys a
healthy extra pawn. He can already consider preparing the thematic e4-e5. 1/2 
(46) Colovic,A (2502)-Danchevski,O (2388) Struga 2013}) ({Too passive is} 12...
Ra8 {In such positions, I like} 13. a4 $1 {taking the b5-square under control
and preparing to establish a light-squared blockade on the queenside. The game
might continue} Nbd7 14. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4]} Ne8 15. Ra3 $1 {[%cal Gc3b5,Gb2b3,
Gd2c4] Another typical move in such structures. By removing the rook from the
long diagonal, White is planning to continue with Nb5, followed by Nc4 and
b2-b3, thus blocking the queenside.} Nc7 16. Nc4 {Being on c4, the knight
supports either a4-a5 or f2-f4 followed by e4-e5.} {The idea} Ne5 {is well met
by} 17. Nb6 Ra5 {blocking the a4-pawn. Otherwise, White will play a4-a5.} 18.
f4 $16 {White has a big advantage.}) ({Dubious is} 12... Rb6 $6 {when White
can proceed with his typical knight transfer to c4 -} 13. Nd2 Nbd7 14. Nc4 Rb7
15. a4 $1 {Once again, we see this thematic idea.} Qa8 {[%cal Gd7b6] Black is
preparing the challenge the c4-knight via the b6-square.} ({The immediate} 
15... Nb6 $2 {runs into} 16. Na5 $18 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Ga5c6] when installing
the knight on c6 will prove decisive.}) 16. Ra3 $1 {Again, White applies the
