1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 Bb7 {With this move, Black
immediately puts pressure on d5. He is planning to completely destroy White's
centre by playing ...e7-e6. White, however, is just in time to support the
d5-pawn.} 6. Nc3 e6 {This is the most logical way to justify the move 5...Bb7.
The alternatives mostly lead to transpositions.} ({The line} 6... axb5 7. Bxb5
Qa5 8. Bd2 {[%emt 0:00:02] transposes to Chapter 2.}) ({An independent option
is} 6... Qa5 7. Bd2 Qb6 $6 {Playing ...Qb6 without taking on b5 is dubious.} ({
Black usually plays} 7... axb5 {when after} 8. Bxb5 {we have a transposition
to Chapter 2.}) {I suggest the rare} 8. Na4 $1 {making use of the fact that
Black didn't play . ..axb5.} Qd6 ({The alternative} 8... Qc7 {runs into} 9. Rc1
d6 10. b4 $18 {with a winning position for White.}) 9. Rc1 axb5 10. Nxc5 Bxd5 {
So far we have been following the game 1-0 (33) Graf,A (2595)-Hadzimanolis,A 
(2301) Kavala 2007. Now, the most convincing would have been} 11. Ne4 $1 Qa6
12. Nxf6+ exf6 13. a4 Qb7 14. axb5 Be7 15. f3 O-O 16. Bd3 $16 {with a healthy
extra pawn.}) 7. e4 axb5 {This is the main continuation. The idea is to meet 8.
Bxb5 with 8... Qa5, winning the pawn back.} ({The main alternative is} 7...
exd5 8. exd5 Bd6 {Played in the spirit of the so-called Snake Benoni. By
leaving the e-file open, Black is planning to continue with ...0-0 followed by
...Re8. White, however, completes the development just in time.} ({Too passive
is} 8... d6 {White can just keep developing his pieces.} 9. Bc4 Be7 10. Nge2 {
In such positions, with e4-square available, I prefer to develop the knight
via e2. Later on, White can transfer the knight to e4 via the g3-square.} O-O
11. O-O Nbd7 12. b3 {Anticipating 12...Nb6.} Nb6 13. bxa6 Bxa6 {This position
occurred in the game. 1/2 (32) Bjelobrk, I-Ker, A (2320) Wanganui 1998. Now,
the simplest would have been} 14. Bxa6 Rxa6 15. Re1 $16 {[%cal Gd1d3,Gc1f4,
Ge2g3] Black does not have compensation for the pawn. On the other hand,
White's play is pretty straightforward. He is planning to increase the
pressure with simple moves such as Qd3, Bf4, Ng3-e4.}) ({Black does not have
time for} 8... g6 $2 {which was played in the game 1-0 (22) Wang, R (2496)
-Szilagyi, Z (2177) Budapest 2000. White could have prevented ...Bg7 by means
of} 9. Bf4 $1 {when Black should start with} d6 ({The point is that} 9... Bg7
$2 {runs into} 10. Bd6 Qb6 11. Qe2+ Kd8 12. Qe7+ Kc8 13. Bxc5 $18 {and White
is winning.}) 10. Bc4 $18 {White has an extra pawn and a positional advantage.}
) 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Be2 {It turns out that Black cannot prevent White from
castling.} axb5 11. Nxb5 {This move is possible because of the unprotected
position of the d6-bishop. The only game in which this position occurred
continued} Qb6 12. Nc3 Na6 13. O-O Rfe8 14. b3 $16 {White enjoys a healthy
extra pawn.1-0 (51) Inkiov, V (2485) -Philippe,C (2417) Cap d'Agde 2010}) ({
Weak is} 7... g6 $2 {0-1 (23) Ivanchuk, V (2726)-Christiansen, J (2495) Riadh
2017. White can play} 8. Bg5 {[%cal Ge4e5] threatening e4-e5.} h6 9. Bh4 g5 10.
Bg3 Bg7 11. h4 $16 {Black's position is very difficult. Besides being a pawn
down, his kingside is seriously weakened.}) ({In this concrete position, the
move} 7... Qa5 {does not make much sense.} 8. Bd2 Qb6 {1/2 (53) Jelen,I (2400)
-Zelic,M (2345) Tucepi 1996} ({Bad is} 8... axb5 $2 {in view of} 9. e5 Ng8 10.
Nxb5 Qb6 11. d6 $18 {when White is completely winning.}) 9. a4 $1 {Typically
for this line, White is giving the pawn back. Later on, he will develop an
initiative by using the activity of his pieces.} exd5 10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Nxd5
Bxd5 12. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Ge2f4,Gf1d3] A key move. White is planning to follow
with Nf4 and Bd3. Black will lose another tempo due to the unprotected
d5-bishop.} Be7 13. Nf4 Bb7 14. Bd3 $36 {White's initiative is very dangerous.
The queen can also enter the attack via the g4-square.}) ({Playing} 7... Qb6 $2
{without first provoking Bd2, is pointless. White can just play} 8. a4 axb5 9.
Bxb5 $18 {with a decisive advantage.}) 8. Bxb5 Qa5 {We have reached the first
critical position for the variation. Black is threatening to win the pawn back
by means of ...Nxe4 or even ...exd5. White's most popular move is 9.Qe2
keeping the extra pawn. I don't like this approach since 9.Qe2 does not
contribute to the development. According to my understanding of the position,
White should give the pawn back and fight for the initiative. By taking the
e4-pawn, Black will actually lose two tempis - one move to take the pawn and
another one to take care of the hanging e4-knight. Therefore, I recommend} 9.
Nge2 $1 {supporting the c3-knight and preparing to castle.} Nxe4 10. O-O {
White has an overwhelming advantage in the development without sacrificing a
single pawn for that (the material is equal). If Black manages to play ...Be7
followed by ...0-0, without compromising his position, he will be doing fine.
This plan, however, is not easy to achieve.} Nd6 {The most popular
continuation but not the strongest one.} ({A natural approach would be} 10...
Be7 {planning to follow with ...0-0} 11. a4 $1 {Overprotecting the b5-bishop
and forcing Black to spend another tempo by moving his knight. The only game
in which this position occurred went} Nxc3 12. Nxc3 O-O 13. Re1 {White has
more space and better development. Black is still struggling to develop his
b8-knight which is tied to the defence of the d7-pawn. White can already
consider developing a kingside initiative.} Qc7 14. Qg4 {[%cal Gc1f4]} Bf6 15.
Bf4 Qb6 16. Qg3 exd5 ({Accepting the pawn by playing} 16... Bxd5 {does not
solve the problems either. A possible line would be} 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Rad1 Nc6
19. Bc7 Qb7 20. Bd6 Rfe8 21. Bxc5 $16 {White has a huge advantage due to his
bishop pair and better pawn structure.}) 17. Bc7 $16 {[%cal Gb5d3] White's
advantage is obvious. After isolating the black queen, he can start playing on
the kingside by means of Bd3 on the next move.1-0 (71) Zhai,M (2358)-Vaishali,
R (2338) Xingtai 2019}) ({Black is not ready for} 10... exd5 $2 11. Nxd5 Na6
12. Nec3 $1 {Now, the e-file is available for the rook.} Nd6 {Up to this point,
we have been following the game 1-0 (25) Flom, G (2448)-Tomasi, A (2324)
Bastia 2017} ({After} 12... Nxc3 $2 {, White gives mate in 6!} 13. Nf6+ Ke7 14.
Ng8+ Rxg8 15. Bg5+ Ke6 16. Qxd7+ Ke5 17. f4+ Ke4 18. Qd3#) (12... Nc7 13. Nxc7+
Qxc7 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Re1 $18) {White's most energetic move would have been}
13. Bg5 $1 {[%cal Gf1e1]} f6 14. Nxf6+ gxf6 15. Bxf6 Rg8 16. Qh5+ Rg6 17. Bd3
$18 {Black is collapsing.}) ({After} 10... Nxc3 11. Nxc3 Be7 {White should
already open the position by means of} 12. dxe6 fxe6 {as was in the game 1-0 
(65) Korsunsky, Y (2415)-El Ghazali, Y (2335) Tanta 1998. Here, the normal} 13.
Be3 $16 {would have given White a strong initiative. Black's central pawns are
shaky while the king remains in the centre.}) 11. Ba4 $1 {Avoiding the
exchange of the light-squared bishop seems to be the best way to keep the
pressure.} Be7 ({The game in which White played 11.Ba4 continued} 11... exd5 $2
12. Re1 $1 Be7 13. Nf4 $18 {with a winning attack.1-0 (28) Bakic,R (2380)
-Pantelic,S (2170) Belgrade 2007}) 12. Bf4 {White creates problems with every
move. Now, the threat is dxe6 followed by Bxd6. The d6-knight turns out to be
vulnerable.} Qb6 ({Supporting the knight with} 12... Ra6 {runs into the
following tricky idea:} 13. a3 O-O 14. b4 $1 {The point is that after} cxb4
$140 $6 15. axb4 Qxb4 $2 {, White is winning a piece by means of} 16. Rb1 Qa5
17. Bxd6 Bxd6 18. Rxb7 $18) ({The a4-bishop is not vulnerable after} 12... exd5
{since White can play} 13. Nxd5 $1 Bxd5 ({Black is not winning a piece with} 
13... Qxa4 $2 {because after,} 14. Nxe7 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 {[%csl Rd6] , the
d6-knight is also hanging.} Nc4 16. Nf5 g6 17. Rac1 gxf5 18. Rxc4 $18 {Black's
structure is awful. White has a winning advantage.}) 14. Nc3 $1 {A very useful
intermediate move.} Bc6 15. Bxc6 Nxc6 16. Bxd6 O-O 17. Bxe7 Nxe7 18. Qxd7 $16 {
Black does not have compensation for the pawn.}) 13. Ng3 O-O ({Accepting the
