1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 e6 {This move fits into the
spirit of the Blumenfeld Gambit. By exchanging the d5-pawn, Black wants to
obtain a strong pawn centre. Contrary to the system with 5...Bb7, this time
White cannot support the d5-pawn by means of e3-e4. From a theoretical point
of view, I consider this system to be one of the most challenging antidotes to
5.e3. At this point, my suggestion is} 6. Nc3 {White keeps control of the
d5-square as long as possible. Black is forced to clarify the situation in the
centre since White is ready to play e3-e4.} ({Another decent option is} 6. dxe6
fxe6 7. Nc3 d5 8. Nf3 {transposing into the Blumenfeld Gambit.}) 6... exd5 ({
Once again, various transpositions are possible. For example, after} 6... Bb7 {
White can play} 7. e4 {obtaining a position which was covered in Chapter 3.}) (
{Another transposition arises after} 6... axb5 7. Bxb5 Bb7 ({An independent
option is} 7... Qa5 $6 {when the simplest solution would be} 8. dxe6 fxe6 9.
Nge2 {White has a fantastic version of the Blumenfeld Gambit. Black still
hadn't played ...d7-d5 while the queen is misplaced on a5. A possible
follow-up is} Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. a4 Na6 12. e4 $16 {White is much better due
to his extra pawn and good central control. 1-0 (23) Graf, A (2574)-Weiss, M 
(2052) Germany 2016}) 8. e4 Qa5 9. Nge2 {This position was dealt with in
Chapter 3.}) 7. Nxd5 Bb7 {Black should remove the d5-knight as soon as
possible. The alternatives are not good.} ({After} 7... axb5 8. Bxb5 {, White
manages to hold the d5-square. For example, after} Bb7 ({Even worse is} 8...
Nxd5 9. Qxd5 {This position has occurred in three games so far. In all of them,
Black played} Qa5+ {which loses on the spot after} 10. Bd2 Qxb5 11. Qxa8 Ba6
12. O-O-O $18) 9. Bc4 {It turns out that Black cannot increase his pressure on
d5. After} Be7 {, White's best option is} 10. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Ge2c3] followed by
Nec3, thus providing additional support for the d5-knight. The only game
featuring this position continued} Nxd5 11. Bxd5 Bxd5 12. Qxd5 Qa5+ 13. Bd2 Qa6
14. O-O $18 {with a decisive advantage for White. 1-0 (41) Tukmakov,V (2540)
-Bednarski,J (2400) Decin 1977}) 8. Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Nf3 Be7 {Black is planning
to play ...d7-d5 after castling.} ({The alternative} 9... Bd6 {trying to
immediately create kingside pressure does not look natural. Blocking the
d-pawn will spoil Black's coordination. At this point, I suggest} 10. Bd2 {
[%cal Gd2c3] with the idea of activating the problematic bishop via the
c3-square.} Qxb2 11. Rc1 Qf6 ({Weak is} 11... c4 $2 {1-0 (38) Moormann,
J-Eimers, J Germany 1990. White achieves a winning position with the simple} 12.
Bxc4 axb5 13. Bb3 $18) ({Relatively the best option for Black is} 11... Be7 {
when after} 12. a4 axb5 13. Bc3 Qa2 14. Bxb5 $36 {White keeps the initiative.})
12. Bc3 {This position occurred in two old games played in 1975. Of course, in
modern computer times, such a position is not playable for Black.} Bxf3 ({
The other game saw} 12... Qe7 13. a4 axb5 14. axb5 Bc7 15. Bc4 O-O 16. Bd5 $16
{with a big positional advantage for White. 1-0 (23) Bagirov, V-Machulsky, A
Cheliabinsk 1975}) 13. gxf3 Be5 14. Bxe5 Qxe5 15. Bg2 Qc7 {Until now, we have
been following the game 1-0 (28) Bagirov, V-Shereshevski, M Baku 1975. Here,
White's simplest continuation would have been} 16. O-O axb5 17. Qd5 Nc6 18.
Rxc5 O-O 19. Rxb5 $16 {with a healthy extra pawn.}) 10. Be2 axb5 {Forcing
White to lose a tempo.} ({A more flexible approach is} 10... O-O {keeping open
the option of playing ...axb5. This move is covered in the next chapter.}) 11.
Bxb5 O-O 12. O-O {This is the critical position of the variation. Quite
obviously, Black will play ...d7-d5 with or without preparation. I analyze two
main moves - 12...Rd8 and 12...d5.} Rd8 ({It is very important to understand
how to handle the structure arising after} 12... d5 {Black hopes that his
strong centre will compensate the missing pawn. After activating his pieces,
he will try to open the position by means of ...d5-d4. Additionally, White's
dark-squared bishop is a bit problematic. On the other hand, White is a pawn
up and does not have weaknesses. My analysis shows that with a precise play
from White, Black's compensation is not enough. At this point, I came up with
a new idea -} 13. Bd3 $1 $146 {[%cal Gc1d2] A very subtle move. White improves
the position of his light-squared bishop and prepares Bd2 (since the bishop is
no longer on b5, White can always answer ...Qxb2 with Rb1). After many hours
of analysis, I realized that White's ideal setup is Bd3, Bd2, and Qc2.
Afterwards, White can start advancing his a-pawn. Additionally, depending on
the concrete circumstances, White can attack the pawn centre by means of e3-e4
or b2-b4 (when trying to weaken the d4-square). Black's ...d5-d4 is usually
answered with Be4 or e3-e4. White plays Bc3 in positions where the advance ...
d5-d4 is not favourable for Black. All these ideas are very well illustrated
in the lines that follow.} Nc6 {The most natural move. Black connects the
rooks and increases the control of the d4-square.} (13... Rd8 14. Bd2 Nc6 {
transposes}) 14. Bd2 $1 Qxb2 {Taking the pawn seems to be the most principled
approach. In order to demonstrate the typical ideas in such positions, I will
examine the alternatives.} ({For example,} 14... h6 {is a move that Black is
going to make sooner or later since White is going to attack the h7-pawn by
means of Qc2.} 15. Qc2 {The desired setup is completed. Since Black has a wide
choice, it would be impossible to deal with every single move. We are going to
on some example lines which show the general methods of playing in such
positions.} ({As mentioned above, White should refrain from} 15. Bc3 $2 {
when Black can play} d4 {under favourable circumstances. It seems that White
can win a pawn with} 16. exd4 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 {Nevertheless, after}
Qg5 19. f3 Rfd8 $17 {[%csl Rd3,Rd4] Black has a huge advantage since White's
bishops are hanging.}) ({Premature is} 15. e4 $2 {due to} c4 {with an
advantage for Black.}) 15... Rab8 {Creating pressure along the b-file is a
typical idea in such structures.} ({Another playable move is} 15... Bd6 {
improving the position of the bishop. Black is ready to expand on the kingside
by means of ...g7-g5-g4.} 16. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Ga5a6] Since the bishop covers
the b4-square, White can start advancing the a-pawn.} g5 {[%cal Gg5g4]} ({
Another idea is} 16... Rfb8 {[%cal Gb7a6] planning to exchange the
light-squared bishops via a6.} 17. Rfc1 $1 {A subtle positional move. In a
case of ...Ba6, White is planning to exchange the bishops and follow with Bc3.
When the b7-bishop is not on the board, White does not fear to provoke...d5-d4.
} ({Less precise is} 17. Rfe1 {since e1 would be a good retreat square for the
bishop. For example, after} Ba6 18. Bc3 d4 19. exd4 cxd4 {The bishop does not
have the e1-square.} 20. Bd2 Bxd3 21. Qxd3 Rxb2 $132) 17... Ba6 ({If Black
refrains from ...Ba6 by playing} 17... Ra7 {[%cal Gb7a8], White can just
follow with his general plan - pushing the a-pawn.} 18. a5 Ba8 19. b3 Nb4 20.
Bxb4 {The knight should always be taken. Even the rook transfer to g4 is not
dangerous in this position. For instance, after} Rxb4 21. a6 Rg4 $2 {White can
just play} 22. h3 {kicking the rook back.}) 18. Bxa6 Rxa6 19. Bc3 d4 20. exd4
cxd4 21. Be1 $16 {White has a big advantage due to the connected passed pawns
on the queenside. At the same time, Black's d-pawn is not dangerous.}) ({
The immediate} 16... Ba6 {can be answered with} 17. Rfd1 {[%csl Rd5][%cal
Gd2c3] underlining the weakness of the d5-pawn.}) 17. h3 $1 {White cannot
allow ...g5-g4 because the f3-knight is the only piece which protects the king.
} Rfb8 18. a5 {When Black does not have a concrete idea, White follows with
his plan.} Bc8 {Planning ...Bxh3. As the bishop left the long diagonal, White
can react with} 19. Bc3 {when the following sequence is possible:} d4 20. exd4
cxd4 21. Bh7+ $1 {Important intermediate move. White wishes that the black
king would be placed along the a1-h8 diagonal.} Kf8 {Sidestepping White's idea.
} ({The point was that after} 21... Kg7 {White can play} 22. Bd2 Bxh3 23. Be4
Bd7 24. Bxc6 Bxc6 25. Nxd4 $18 {Taking with the queen is impossible in view of
Bc3.}) 22. Bd2 Bxh3 23. Be4 Bd7 24. g3 $16 {White keeps everything under
control. Black cannot attack on the kingside while White's passed pawns will
decide the game.}) 16. b3 {By creating an immediate pressure on the b-file,
Black anticipates the advance of the a-pawn. White, however, can play} Ba8 17.
Rfe1 {[%cal Ge3e4] planning e3-e4.} Nb4 18. Bxb4 Rxb4 19. Rab1 {[%cal Ga2a3,
Ge3e4] The idea is to play e3-e4 immediately or after a2-a3. I have examined
the following sequence:} Rfb8 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Gc5c4,Gb4b2]} 20. e4 c4 21. bxc4
dxe4 22. Bxe4 Rb2 23. Bxa8 Rxc2 24. Rxb8+ Bf8 25. g3 Rb2 26. Ree8 Rxb8 27. Rxb8
$16 {[%cal Ga8d5,Gb8b7] White has a huge advantage. He can start pressing the
f7-pawn by means of Bd5 followed by Rb7. Additionally, the a-pawn will become
very dangerous.}) ({In this structure, Black often plays} 14... Rfd8 {with the
idea of playing ...d5-d4 in the suitable moment. As we are going to witness,
however, this advance does not work well against White's setup.} 15. Qc2 h6 16.
a4 $1 {Since everything is under control, White can start advancing the a-pawn.
} Bc8 {[%cal Gc8g4] planning to challenge the f3-knight by playing ...Bg4.} ({
In response to} 16... d4 {White can just play} 17. Rfe1 $1 {putting an
indirect pressure along the e-file and planning e3-e4 if the black knight
leaves the c6-square.} dxe3 ({In response to} 17... Na5 {White should play} 18.
e4 $16 {with an obvious positional advantage. It is important to know that} c4
{does not work in view of} 19. Bxc4 Nxc4 20. Qxc4 Rac8 21. Qb5 $16 {when White
has two extra pawns.}) ({White's last move is a kind of prophylactic against
the typical} 17... Ne5 $2 {Now, after} 18. Nxe5 Qxe5 19. exd4 $18 {White is
winning.}) 18. Rxe3 Nb4 19. Bxb4 cxb4 20. Rae1 Bd6 21. Bh7+ Kh8 22. Be4 $16 {
After neutralizing the b7-bishop, White is better.}) 17. Bc3 $1 {This move is
already possible because Black's light-squared bishop has left the b7-square.
After} d4 18. exd4 cxd4 19. Bd2 Nb4 20. Bxb4 Bxb4 21. Qe2 $14 {Black does not
have sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) 15. Rb1 Qa3 16. Qc2 $1 {An
important intermediate move. Besides protecting the d3-bishop, White is
attacking the h7-pawn. A possible follow-up would be} Bc8 17. Rb6 Nb4 18. Bxh7+
Kh8 19. Bxb4 cxb4 20. Bd3 Qxa2 21. Qc6 $36 {with a dangerous initiative for
White. In the future, the black king might prove quite vulnerable.}) ({The move
} 12... Qe6 {was played in the game 1/2 (16) Harsha, B (2134)-Padhya, S (2234)
Lucknow 2013. At this point, White could have opted for} 13. a4 {with the idea
to meet} d5 $140 {with} 14. b4 $1 {which is a typical way to weaken the
d4-square.} cxb4 15. Nd4 $16 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc1d2,Ga1b1,Gd2b4] White has a
big advantage. His next moves are Bd2 and Rb1.}) {Against 12...Rd8, I suggest}
13. e4 $1 {taking advantage of the fact that Black has delayed the advance ...
d7-d5. At the same time, White prepares Bg5.} Bxe4 14. Bg5 Qxb2 15. Bxe7 Re8 {
So far, we have been following the game 1/2 (42) Rizzardi, J (2391)-Dos Santos,
M (2420) ICCF email 2006. In this position, I have tried to improve White's
play with} 16. Re1 $1 $146 {The position becomes very concrete. I think that
Black should opt for the following sequence} Rxe7 17. Ng5 Qxb5 18. Rxe4 Rxe4 (
18... Nc6 19. Qh5 Rxe4 20. Qxf7+ {transposes}) 19. Qh5 Nc6 ({Another
possibility is} 19... Qc4 20. Qxh7+ Kf8 21. Nxe4 Rxa2 22. Rf1 Ra6 $1 {For a
human is very very difficult to find this optimal defence. Black takes the
d6-square under control and threatens ...Rh6.} ({After} 22... Nc6 $2 23. Nd6 $1
Qc3 (23... Qe6 24. Nf5 $18) 24. Qh8+ Ke7 25. Nf5+ Ke6 26. Qe8+ Kf6 27. Nd6 $18
{White is winning.}) 23. Qh8+ Ke7 24. Ng5 $40 {[%cal Gh8g7,Gf1e1] From a
practical point of view, this position is lost for Black because of the weak
king.}) 20. Qxf7+ Kh8 21. Nxe4 $36 {I am sure detailed engine analysis will
