1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 e6 6. Nc3 exd5 7. Nxd5 Bb7 8.
Nxf6+ Qxf6 9. Nf3 Be7 10. Be2 O-O {In my opinion, this is the most challenging
continuation. Black is planning to follow with ...d7-d5 without taking on b5.
At the same time, White should reckon the move ...axb5 at any moment. If White
decides to release the tension by taking on a6, then Black usually recaptures
with the knight.} ({The alternative} 10... Qe6 $6 {[%csl Rb5][%cal Ga8a2,Ge6a2,
Ga6b5] seems to be dubious. Black provokes a2-a4 by putting indirect pressure
on the a2-pawn. At the same time, the f6-square is now available for the
bishop. On the other hand, White would like to play a2-a4. In this way, he
grabs space on the queenside and supports the b5-pawn. The next few moves seem
logical.} 11. a4 axb5 12. Bxb5 Bf6 13. O-O O-O 14. Re1 {[%cal Ge3e4] This
position occurred in two games. White prepares the thematic e3-e4.} Nc6 {
The most logical move. Black completes the development and connects the rooks.
He is now ready for active actions.} ({The other game saw} 14... Rd8 $2 {
which allows} 15. e4 $1 {White's advantage is already significant. He has an
extra pawn and good control of the centre. In the game, Black lost quickly
after} Bxe4 $2 16. Ng5 Bxg5 17. Bxg5 Qg6 18. Qg4 d5 19. f3 Bf5 20. Bxd8 {
1-0 (20) Berkes,F (2664)-Fitzsimons,D (2389) Southend 2015}) 15. Ra3 $1 {
[%cal Ga3d3] The rook enters the game! This move is even more precise than the
immediate e3-e4. In a suitable moment, White can play Rd3, putting pressure on
the d-pawn.} Rfd8 ({The standard} 15... d5 {is well met by} 16. Qc2 {[%cal
Gc1d2] followed by Bd2. We reach a structure similar to the one from the
previous chapter.}) 16. e4 Nd4 17. Nxd4 Bxd4 18. Rd3 d5 {So far we have been
following the game 1-0 (44) Basso, P (2494)-Loiacono, A (2297) Spilimbergo
2018. Now, the simple} 19. exd5 Qxd5 20. Qf3 $16 {would have secured a big
advantage. After the exchange of the queens, White extra pawn is getting very
important.}) 11. bxa6 {I think that this is White's most precise move. The
idea is to answer 11...Nxa6 with 12.Bd2 followed by Bc3. The b2-pawn cannot be
taken in view of Rb1, making use of the unprotected b7-bishop. This position
has been reached in only three games. All of them continued} Nxa6 {which is
objectively not the best move. We shall take a look at the alternatives.} ({
The provocative} 11... Rxa6 $5 {also makes sense. Black brings the rook into
play via the 6th rank.} 12. Bd2 {The development of the dark-squared bishop is
White's most important task.} ({Accepting the sacrifice is dangerous. For
example, after} 12. Bxa6 Bxa6 13. Qc2 Nc6 14. Bd2 Qe6 $44 {Black has good
compensation for the exchange since the white king is stuck in the centre.})
12... Qg6 13. O-O Rd6 14. Qc1 Qf5 {[%cal Gd6g6] preparing ...Rg6. It turns out
that White can neutralize Black's threats by means of} 15. Ne1 {[%cal Gf2f3]
with the idea of f2-f3.} Rg6 ({Anticipating the move f2-f3 with} 15... Re8 {
is not a problem for White. The game might continue} 16. f3 Bg5 17. f4 Bf6 18.
Bc3 $14 {White managed to coordinate his pieces. The pressure on e3 is not
enough compensation for the pawn. Increasing pressure is not easy. For example,
after} Bxc3 19. Qxc3 Rde6 $6 {White can play} 20. Bd3 Qh5 21. Nc2 $16 {with a
full control of the position.}) 16. f3 Bd6 {This is the most challenging setup.
Now, White should be precise.} ({After} 16... Qh5 17. Rf2 Rh6 18. g3 Bd6 19. f4
$16 {Black's attack is neutralized while White's extra pawn becomes
significant.}) 17. e4 Qh5 (17... Qe5 {is well met by} 18. f4 $1 Qxe4 19. Bf3
Qd4+ 20. Be3 Qb4 21. a3 Qb5 $1 {A precise computer defence.} ({After} 21... Qb6
22. f5 Rf6 23. Bxb7 Qxb7 24. Bg5 $18 {White is winning.}) 22. a4 $1 {An
important intermediate move.} ({The difference with 21...Qb6 becomes obvious
after} 22. f5 $6 Ba6 $1 23. Rf2 Rf6 {when White does not have time to play Bg5.
}) 22... Qb4 23. Bxb7 Qxb7 24. f5 Rg4 25. Qd1 Qe4 26. Rf3 $14 {White keeps
some advantage due to the strong a4-pawn and miscoordinated black pieces.}) 18.
Bf4 $16 {This is the point. After the exchange of the dark-squared bishops,
Black does not have an attack.}) ({Another option is} 11... Bxa6 {After the
exchange of the light-squares bishops, however, I don't believe in Black's
compensation. In this type of positions, the pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal
is a very important factor.} 12. O-O Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Nc6 14. a3 d5 15. Qc2 $14 {
[%cal Gc1d2] White is planning to complete the development by means of Bd2.
Black's play is far from obvious.}) ({The computer suggests} 11... Be4 {
which is not very strong in my opinion. Once again, White can settle for an
exchange of the light-squared bishops by playing} 12. Bd3 d5 ({Another option
is} 12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nxa6 14. O-O Nb4 {Black should play energetically.
Otherwise, White will complete the development, remaining with an extra pawn.}
15. Qb1 {[%csl Rb4][%cal Gc1d2,Gd2c3,Ga2a3]} Qg6 {[%cal Gb4d3] Planning to
install a knight on d3. At this point, White should opt for the following
sequence -} 16. a3 Nd3 17. Bd2 Bf6 18. Bc3 Bxc3 19. bxc3 Rfb8 20. Qa2 $14 {
The activity of Black's pieces does not fully compensate for the missing pawn.}
) 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Nd2 {White has an extra pawn and a better pawn structure.
He just needs to complete the development. The following sequence seems to be
pretty logical.} Qg6 15. O-O Nxa6 16. Qc2 Nb4 17. Qxe4 Qxe4 18. Nxe4 Rxa2 19.
Rxa2 Nxa2 20. Bd2 $16 {White remains a pawn up. Black's compensation is
problematic.}) ({The most challenging continuation seems to be} 11... Bc6 $1 {
Black is now planning to follow with ...Nxa6. The idea behind 11...Bc6 is to
remove the bishop from the vulnerable b7-square. In this position, 12.Bd2 can
be answered with 12...Qxb2. In this case, 13.Rb1 would be pointless since
Black's bishop is not on b7.} 12. a7 $1 {As it will become clear, in some
cases, on the a7-square the rook might prove vulnerable.} Rxa7 13. O-O Na6 14.
a3 Rb8 {This is the most logical continuation. By increasing the pressure on
b2, Black is trying to prevent the development of the c1-bishop.} ({The idea
behind 12.a7! becomes clear after} 14... Qe6 15. Bd2 Rb8 16. Bc3 Nc7 17. b4 $1
{[%csl Ra7][%cal Ga1a7] By playing this thematic move, White makes use of the
unprotected a7-rook. The problem becomes clear after} cxb4 $2 18. axb4 ({
An alternative is} 18. Nd4 Qg6 19. Nxc6 dxc6 20. Bxb4 Bxb4 21. axb4 $16 {
with an obvious advantage.}) 18... Rxa1 19. Qxa1 $16 {The b4-pawn cannot be
taken since g7 is hanging.}) 15. Re1 {[%cal Ge2f1,Ge3e4] Given the fact that
Black focused on the queenside, White starts preparing the advance e3-e4.} Qg6
({The thematic} 15... Qe6 {[%cal Ge7f6] planning ...Bf6 exposes the queen to
the opposition with the e1-rook. Therefore, White can follow with} 16. e4 $1 {
without any preparations. After} Bf6 17. e5 Be7 18. Bd3 $16 {White has a big
advantage due to the domination in the centre.}) 16. Bf1 {[%cal Gf3e5]
Overprotecting the g2-pawn and freeing the knight. Another idea is e3-e4.} Be4
17. Ne5 Qe6 18. Nd3 $14 {White's position is already very stable. Black's
counterplay is not obvious.}) 12. Bd2 $1 {[%csl Rb7] The most precise move.
Since the black bishop is on b7, White has time to execute the manoeuvre
Bd2-c3. Black's compensation is problematic. The position is not concrete and
Black has a wide choice of moves. Below, I just provide a sample line which
illustrates some of the typical ideas.} Qg6 13. Bc3 $1 {The g2-pawn is
untouchable in view of Rg1.} Rfd8 14. O-O Nc7 {[%cal Gc7d5] Black is planning
to challenge the stability of the c3-bishop by means of ...Nd5.} ({Black can
also play} 14... Be4 {[%cal Gd7d5] with the idea of playing ...d7-d5 without
closing the diagonal of the bishop. In my opinion, White's most solid
continuation is} 15. g3 {[%cal Gf3e5] preparing Ne5.} d5 16. Ne5 Qe6 {Keeping
the e5-knight under control.} ({After} 16... Qb6 {, White can exchange the
light-squared bishops by means of} 17. Bf3 $16) 17. Bg4 ({In this position,
the move} 17. Bf3 {is not that effective because of} Bf6 {making use of the
unstable e5-knight.}) 17... f5 18. Be2 $16 {[%csl Re4] White has an obvious
advantage. He can already consider the manoeuvre Nd3-f4. Also, at any moment,
Black should reckon with f2-f3.}) ({The immediate} 14... d5 {is well met by}
15. Qb1 $1 Qe6 16. Re1 $16 {when White has an extra pawn and a stable position.
}) 15. a4 $1 {Since Black's play is time-consuming, White can start advancing
the a-pawn.} Nd5 16. Bd2 Nf6 17. a5 Ne4 18. Qc2 $14 {White has a stable
position with a safe king and no weaknesses. Additionally, the a5-pawn is an
important asset. It is not clear how Black will develop his counterplay.} *

