1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 g6 {This is by far the most
popular reaction to 5.e3. This move fits better into the spirit of the Benko
Gambit since in most of the cases Black is trying to achieve a typical Benko
structure. The next few moves are obvious.} 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O {Of course,
Black could have played ...d7-d6 earlier. The exact move order would not make
a difference since the moves ...Bg7 and ...0-0 will be played in any case. At
this point, White faces a wide choice of moves. My choice is} 8. a4 {which I
consider being the most flexible move. White refrains from moving his
f1-bishop because Black will answer with ...axb5 causing a loss of a tempo. As
we know from the Pawn Structures section, the advance a2-a4 is very useful
since it contributes to the blockade of the queenside. Additionally, with his
last move, White also prepares the advance e3-e4.} ({The point is that the
immediate} 8. e4 $6 {can be met by} axb5 {when} 9. Bxb5 $6 {runs into the
thematic} Nxe4 $1 {with a big advantage for Black.}) {In my opinion, Black's
strongest continuation is 8...d6, entering the classical Benko structure. This
move will be dealt with in the next chapters. In this chapter, I examine the
attempt to put pressure on the centre by means of} 8... Bb7 ({The alternative} 
8... e6 9. e4 Bb7 10. Be2 {transposes to 8...Bb7.}) 9. e4 e6 10. Be2 {White is
about to complete the development. Additionally, he has good control of the
centre. In order to create counterplay, Black should immediately open the
position.} exd5 ({The alternative move order} 10... axb5 11. Bxb5 exd5 12. exd5
{leads to the main line.}) 11. exd5 axb5 12. Bxb5 Re8+ {This is by far the
most popular continuation. Black provokes 13.Be3 which will be met with 13...
Ng4.} ({To my surprise, the rare} 12... Qe8+ {is more challenging.} 13. Be3 ({
White does not manage to complete the development by playing} 13. Be2 {since
after} Na6 {the move} 14. O-O {runs into} Nxd5 $1 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 $11 {[%csl Re2]
The position is equal.}) 13... Ng4 14. Qe2 {Contrary to the line starting with
12...Re8+, I think that in this case White should refrain from giving the pawn
back.} ({For a while, similarly to 12...Re8, I was trying to make} 14. O-O {
work. Black's It turns out, however, that Black obtains a very decent
counterplay.} Nxe3 15. fxe3 Qxe3+ 16. Kh1 Na6 $132 {[%csl Gg7][%cal Ga6b4]
This position occurred in the game 1-0 (31) Moroni, L (2562)-Jaksland, T (2264)
Caleta 2019. I think that Black has more than sufficient counterplay due to the
strong g7-bishop and the pressure against the d5-pawn.}) ({The alternative way
to protect the e3-bishop is} 14. Qd2 {Now, however, Black can use the pin
along the e-file by playing} Bh6 {In this case, White will be forced to give
the pawn back.} 15. O-O ({The alternative} 15. Nd1 {is too passive. Black can
proceed with} Na6 16. O-O Nxe3 17. Nxe3 Nc7 {when the pressure on d5 gives
Black good counterplay.}) 15... Bxe3 16. fxe3 Qxe3+ 17. Kh1 Qxd2 18. Nxd2 Ne3
19. Rfc1 d6 20. Nc4 Nxc4 21. Bxc4 Na6 $11 {with equality.}) 14... Nxe3 15. Qxe3
Na6 16. O-O Qxe3 17. fxe3 Nb4 18. e4 {This position has been reached in two
games - Atalik, S - Ivanisevic, I and Kazmierczak, Z - Leonard, A which is a
correspondence game. White managed to retain his extra pawn and to restrict
Black's immediate counterplay. Nevertheless, White's advantage is not big due
to the strong g7-bishop.} d6 {This position was reached in 1/2 (50) Atalik, S 
(2537)-Ivanisevic,I (2611) Ruma 2017} ({The correspondence game went} 18... Ba6
19. Rfd1 $14 {when White keeps his slight advantage. 1/2 (36) Kazmierczak, Z 
(1929)-Leonard,A (2110) ICCF email 2010}) {At this point, White could have
played} 19. Rab1 $1 Ba6 {[%cal Gc5c4,Gb4d3] planning ...c5-c4 followed by ...
Nd3.} 20. Nd2 $1 {[%cal Gd2c4] The knight is heading to c4. An illustrative
line would be} Bd4+ 21. Kh1 Nd3 22. Nc4 Nf2+ 23. Rxf2 Bxf2 24. Nxd6 Bxb5 25.
axb5 Bd4 26. g4 $14 {White keeps better chances due to his dangerous passed
pawns.}) 13. Be3 ({Once again,} 13. Be2 {can be countered with} Na6 14. O-O
Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Bg5 Qb8 17. Qxd5 Rxe2 $132) 13... Ng4 {This is the
point of Black's concept. Without this move, White just completes the
development and enjoys his extra pawn.} ({For example, after} 13... Na6 14.
O-O Ne4 {1-0 (62) Zhukova,N (2450)-Pogonina,N (2471) Plovdiv 2008 White can
just play} 15. Rc1 $16 {keeping everything under control.}) 14. O-O {White
gives the pawn back in order to develop a dangerous initiative. In addition to
his development problems, Black will waste time to regain the pawn.} Nxe3 {
This is the more natural recapture. In this case, the rook will remain in the
game.} ({After} 14... Rxe3 15. fxe3 Nxe3 16. Qd2 Nxf1 17. Rxf1 {, we see that
in order to win the pawn back, Black exchanged his rook and knight. According
to the classical principles, when we are underdeveloped, we shouldn't exchange
the pieces which are already activated. The g7-bishop will not be enough to
neutralize White's kingside initiative. The game might continue} Na6 18. Bc4 $1
{[%cal Gd5d6] By threatening the open the diagonal a2-g8 by means of d5-d6,
White provokes the advance ...d7-d6.} d6 ({Taking the g5-square under control
with} 18... h6 {does not solve the problems. For example, after} 19. Qf4 Nb4
20. Ne5 $16 {Black should part with his dark-squared bishop, thus weakening
the dark squares around the king.}) 19. Ng5 $1 {This move is the point behind
the idea of provoking ...d7-d6. Now, the advance ...f7-f5 can be answered with
Ne6. The attempt to prevent this scenario by means of} Bh6 {runs into the
intermediate} 20. Qf2 $1 {when Black should already play ...f7-f5.} f5 21. Ne6
Qe7 22. Re1 $16 {The e6-knight gives White a big positional advantage.}) 15.
fxe3 Rxe3 16. Qd2 {An important tempo. White connects the rooks and brings the
queen into the game.} Re8 ({The attempt to keep the rook on e3 with} 16... Bh6
{is well met by} 17. Ne5 $1 Rxe5 18. Qxh6 Qe7 19. Qd2 $16 {[%cal Ga1e1]
Followed by Re1 with the idea to exchange Black's only active piece. Later on,
White is going to develop a dangerous kingside initiative.}) 17. Kh1 {It is
useful to remove the king from the dangerous a7-g1 diagonal. In some cases, a
move like ...Bd4+ might prove useful for Black. For example, 17.Ng5? can be
met by 17...Bd4+ followed by ...Be3, winning the knight.} Na6 {Black is trying
to complete the development as soon as possible.} ({Wasting even more time with
} 17... h6 {can hardly be recommended. White's play follows quite naturally.}
18. Rae1 Rxe1 19. Rxe1 Na6 20. d6 $1 {A key move. White opens the a2-g8
diagonal and prepares to invade Black's camp with Re7. The only game in which
this position occurred followed} Nb4 $2 {which turns out to be a decisive
mistake.} ({The most tenacious defence would have been} 20... Qf6 {Even in
this case, however, White can play} 21. Nd5 $1 Qxb2 22. Qxb2 Bxb2 23. Nb6 Rd8
24. Bc4 $16 {[%cal Ge1e7] with a big advantage. The idea is Re7.}) ({Taking
the knight with} 20... Bxf3 {does not help either. After} 21. gxf3 Qf6 22. Qd5
Ra7 23. f4 $18 {White has a decisive advantage since Black's pieces are
completely tied.}) 21. Re7 Nc6 22. Rxf7 $1 {A simple but elegant final shot.}
Qe8 (22... Kxf7 23. Qd5+ Kf8 24. Bc4 {with a mate to follow.}) 23. Bc4 $18 {
1-0 (43) Fier,A (2628)-Rambaldi,F (2513) Biel 2015}) ({An interesting idea is} 
17... Rf8 $146 {[%cal Gd7d6] preparing ...d7-d6. Since this move wastes time,
White can immediately start developing his kingside initiative by means of} 18.
Qf4 {[%cal Gf3g5,Gf4d6]} ({Another possibility is} 18. Rae1 {which is more
positional approach. A possible line would be} d6 19. Qf4 {[%csl Rd6][%cal
Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Gf3g5] Planning to attack the d6-pawn with Nd2-c4 or Ng5-e4.} h6
20. Nd2 Nd7 21. Nc4 ({After} 21. Qxd6 Nb6 {Black's bishop pair provides a good
compensation for the pawn.}) 21... Ne5 22. Nxe5 dxe5 23. Qe3 $14 {White
retains some positional advantage due to his strong passed pawn.}) {At this
point, I have came up with the following sequence} 18... d6 19. Ng5 Nd7 20.
Nxf7 Qe7 21. Qxd6 $1 Rxf7 22. Qxe7 Rxe7 23. d6 Rf7 24. Bc4 Bf6 25. Nd5 Ba6 26.
Nxf6+ Nxf6 27. Bxf7+ Kxf7 28. Rfe1 $16 {White has an obvious advantage.
Supported by the rooks, the d6-pawn can become very dangerous. Moreover, the
black minor pieces are not well coordinated.}) 18. d6 $1 {Once again, we see
this typical idea. White is now ready to play Bc4.} Nb4 19. Bc4 {The pressure
on f7 is decisive. Black cannot deal with White's initiative.} Bf6 {This move
was played in the game 0-1 (66) Gonda, L (2490)-Perunovic, M (2619) Hungary 2016.
As we are going to see, taking the g5-square under control does not help.} ({
In the case of} 19... Nc6 {, White has the powerful} 20. Bxf7+ $1 Kxf7 21. Qd5+
Re6 22. Ng5+ Kg8 23. Nxe6 dxe6 24. Qxe6+ Kh8 25. Rae1 Nd4 26. Qf7 Bc6 27. d7 {
with a winning position. 1-0 (40) Savina, A (2343)-Aranaz Murillo, A (2211)
Benidorm 2011}) {At this point, White could have played} 20. Qh6 {with a
decisive advantage. Below, I provide some short lines as an example.} Rf8 (
20... Bg7 $2 21. Bxf7+ $18) (20... Re6 21. Qf4 $1 Nc2 22. Rad1 $18) 21. Rae1
Ba6 22. Nb5 Nc6 23. b3 $18 {[%cal Gh6f4,Gh2h4,Gf3g5] White is winning. The
idea is simple. Putting pressure on the f-file by means of Qf4 followed by
h2-h4 and Ng5.} *

