1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. a4 d6
{This is by far Black's main move. Under favourable circumstances, he is
planning to proceed with ...axb5 entering the classical Benko structure. In
this chapter, however, we are going to examine another attempt to play in the
centre.} 9. e4 e6 {Black is trying to make use of the fact that White has
wasted time by playing a2-a4 and e2-e3-e4. Therefore, Black will try to open
the centre as soon as possible. This approach, however, does not work
tactically. Black's main moves 9...axb5 and 9...Nbd7 will be covered in the
next chapters.} 10. dxe6 Bxe6 {This is the most principled approach. Black
develops the bishop and prepares to open the centre with the advance ...d6-d5.}
({The alternative recapture} 10... fxe6 {also deserves attention. The idea is
to create a strong pawn centre by means of ...d6-d5. White, however, has an
important resource at his disposal -} 11. e5 $1 {This break is a thematic idea
in such structures. Besides spoiling Black's pawn structure, White is also
planning to exchange the queens. The analysis proves that Black's development
does not compensate the static problems.} dxe5 ({Avoiding the exchange by
means of} 11... Ng4 $2 {does not work. White can just follow with} 12. exd6 {
winning a second pawn. The rest is simple - Be2 and 0-0.} Ne5 ({To the same
position leads} 12... Bb7 13. Be2 Ne5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. O-O $18) 13. Be2 Bb7
14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. O-O $18 {White has a decisive advantage. Black will regain
only one of the pawns. White will remain with an extra pawn and a better pawn
structure.}) 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Be3 $1 {This is the most precise continuation.
White develops the bishop with a tempo and intends to answer 13...Nd5 with 14.
Rd1.} e4 {Opening the diagonal for the g7-bishop seems like the most natural
reaction.} ({As mentioned above,} 13... Nd5 {is well met by} 14. Rd1 axb5 15.
Bxb5 $16 {With a stable advantage due to the active pieces and the better pawn
structure.}) ({Another option is} 13... axb5 14. Bxb5 Bb7 {So far, we have
been following the game 1-0 (44) Mohanakrishnan, B (2121)-Engelberg, J (2157)
ICCF email 2015.} ({The idea} 14... Na6 15. Nxe5 Nd5 {, challenging the
stability of White's knights, can be countered with} 16. Nc6 Rd7 17. O-O Nxc3
18. bxc3 Bxc3 19. Rac1 $16 {White had a big advantage in 1-0 (48) Pheby,
I-Lovholt, T (2351) England 2000}) {At this point, White's best would have been}
15. Ng5 $1 {[%cal Gf2f3,Gg5e4] with the idea to meet} Bd5 ({Bad is} 15... Bxg2
$2 {in view of} 16. Nxe6 Rd6 17. Rg1 Rxe6 18. Rxg2 $18 {White is winning due
to his better structure and powerful bishop pair.}) {with} 16. f3 $16 {[%cal
Gg5e4] establishing a blockade on the e4-square.}) 14. Ng5 h6 15. Ngxe4 Nxe4
16. Nxe4 axb5 17. Bxb5 $16 {White had an obvious advantage in 1-0 (41)
Fritsche, F (2170)-Nonnenmacher, T (1655) GER email 2014.}) 11. Be3 $1 {This
move which discourages the advance ...d6-d5 is White's most precise
continuation. It was employed by the top-player Wesley So as well. This
position occurred in three games. Two of them continued} Qa5 {creating the
threat of ...Nxe4 and reinforcing the advance ...d6-d5.} ({Of course, we shall
examine the complications arising after} 11... d5 12. Bxc5 {The only game in
which this position occurred continued} Re8 {giving White the possibility to
stabilize the centre.} ({I have also examined the exchange sacrifice arising
after} 12... Nxe4 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Nd4 Bd5 15. Bxf8 {Now, Black should decide
how to recapture. In any case, I think that Black does not have enough
compensation for White's serious material advantage.} Qxf8 {[%cal Gf8b4]} ({
The alternative} 15... Bxf8 {is also logical. Once again, White must spend a
tempo on} 16. Qd2 {preventing ...Bb4+. Black's most logical idea is} e3 {
trying to open the position until White's king is in the centre. I have
examined the following sequence} 17. fxe3 Nd7 {Before giving a check with ...
Qh4+, Black waits for the development of the f1-bishop.} ({The immediate} 17...
Qh4+ {can be met with} 18. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2] followed by 19.Bg2.}) 18. Bd3 Qh4+
19. Qf2 Bb4+ 20. Kf1 Qe7 21. Rd1 Ne5 22. Be2 axb5 23. axb5 Nc4 24. Bxc4 Bxc4+
25. Kg1 Bc5 26. h4 $16 {White can finally coordinate his pieces by developing
the rook via h3. Of course, the entire sequence is by no means forced. I share
these analyses in order to give you an idea of how to arrange the pieces in
such positions.}) 16. Qd2 Nd7 17. Be2 e3 {Once again, this break helps Black
to keep White's king in the centre.} 18. fxe3 Bxg2 19. Rg1 Be4 20. bxa6 Qe7 {
[%cal Ge7h4]} 21. Rf1 $16 {planning to meet 21...Qh4+ with Rf2. White's king
is safe in the centre. Additionally, White can rely on his strong d4-knight
and the passed pawns on the queenside. Black does not have enough compensation
for the sacrificed material.}) 13. e5 $1 {Closing the centre is the best
approach to the position. Of course, White is ready to sacrifice one of his
two extra pawns (the e5-one). While Black is wasting time to collect it, White
will complete the development, thus remaining with a healthy extra pawn.} Nbd7
({An alternative way to collect the pawn is} 13... Bg4 {when White can just
follow with} 14. Be2 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Rxe5+ 16. Be3 axb5 17. O-O $16 {White has
two powerful bishops and a huge advantage in the development.}) ({After} 13...
Nfd7 14. Bd4 Bg4 15. Be2 axb5 {, the intermediate} 16. e6 $1 {works very well.
For example -} Rxe6 17. O-O Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Bxd4 19. Qxd4 Nc6 20. Qxd5 $16 {
with a healthy extra pawn.}) 14. Bd4 ({Weak is} 14. exf6 $2 {due to} Nxc5 15.
fxg7 Bh3+ $1 {A very strong move, preventing Be2. Now, after} 16. Ne2 {, Black
can force a draw by perpetual:} Qa5+ 17. Qd2 Nd3+ 18. Kd1 Nxf2+ 19. Ke1 Nd3+
$11) {The next few moves are logical.} 14... Bg4 15. Be2 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Nxe5 17.
O-O axb5 18. Nxb5 Ne4 19. Re1 Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 Bxd4 21. Nxd4 Qb6 22. Nb5 Re6 {
We have been following the game 0-1 (32) Likavsky, T (2470)-Pachow, J (2334)
Oberland 2003. Now, after} 23. Rec1 $16 {White could have secured a big
advantage.}) 12. Bd2 $1 {preventing all the threats related to the pin along
the a5-e1 diagonal.} Qc7 13. Be2 axb5 14. Bxb5 {Since White is ready to
complete the development, Black should play energetically. In the game, he
decided to attack the e4-pawn with} Qb7 15. O-O $1 {This is the point. Wesley
So gives the pawn back in order to overtake the initiative. It turns out that
now Black is the one who is behind in development. The game followed} Nxe4 16.
Nxe4 Qxe4 17. Ng5 Qf5 18. Nxe6 fxe6 19. Bc3 $16 {neutralizing the g7-bishop.
In the resulting position, the b5-bishop will be superior to the black knight.
Additionally, the a5-pawn can become very dangerous soon while Black's central
pawns are shaky. Also, in the future, the Black king might prove vulnerable.
1-0 (25) So, W (2719)-Altschuler, J (2051) Lubbock 2013} *

