1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. a4 d6
9. e4 axb5 {With this move, Black enters the classical Benko structure. The
main alternative is 9...Nbd7 with the idea to take on b5 only when White moves
his f1-bishop. The move 9...Nbd7 will be dealt with in the next chapter. Of
course, we shall deal with some alternatives that Black has on move 9.} ({
Preparing ...e7-e6 with} 9... Bb7 $6 {is dubious in view of} 10. Bf4 $1 {
preventing the advance ...e7-e6. I don't see how Black can create counterplay
in this position. Going for the typical Benko structure by playing 10...axb5
is not good. In such positions, the bishop is poorly placed on b7.} Nbd7 ({
One game saw the creative} 10... Qd7 {which should be answered with} 11. Bd3 ({
The idea of Black's last move can be seen in the line} 11. Be2 $2 Nxe4 12. Nxe4
Qf5 {making use of the hanging pieces in the centre.}) 11... c4 ({After} 11...
axb5 {, White should play} 12. axb5 {reaching the famous structure with a pawn
on b5.} Rxa1 13. Qxa1 c4 14. Bc2 e6 15. dxe6 fxe6 16. O-O) 12. Bc2 axb5 13.
axb5 Rxa1 14. Qxa1 {White is already preparing 0-0 followed by Qa7 or Nd4-c6.
Black's only hope is to attack the centre with} e6 {As we have witnessed on
many occasions, giving the pawn back in order to obtain another advantage is a
typical way of playing against the gambits. At this point, White can opt for}
15. dxe6 fxe6 16. O-O Bxe4 17. Nxe4 Nxe4 18. Be3 $16 {When the bishop pair and
the strong b-pawn give White a clear advantage.}) 11. Be2 Qa5 12. Bd2 $16 {
Black does not have the slightest compensation for the pawn.}) ({Preparing the
advance ...f7-f5 with} 9... Ne8 {only weakens Black's pawn structure. At this
point, I prefer} 10. Bg5 $1 {putting pressure on e7 and protecting the a1-rook.
White is now ready to answer ...axb5 with axb5. After} f5 11. exf5 Bxf5 12. Be2
axb5 13. axb5 Rxa1 14. Qxa1 Nf6 15. O-O $16 {White had a big advantage in 1-0 
(44) Blagojevic,D (2549)-Kasparova,T (2240) Cutro 2005.}) ({Sometimes, Black
plays} 9... Bg4 $6 {which is a positional mistake. By giving his light-squared
bishop for a knight, Black grants White the complete control of the
light-squares.} 10. h3 Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qa5 {Black is planning ...Qb4. White,
however, has enough resources to deal with this idea.} 12. Bd2 Qb4 {This
position occurred in two games of GM Stocek. In both games, White protected the
b2-pawn with 13.Rb1, giving Black time to build his counterplay. At this point,
I suggest an improvement -} 13. bxa6 $1 $146 {[%cal Gf1b5] securing the
b5-square for the bishop.} Nxa6 ({The typical advance} 13... c4 {can be
answered with} 14. Nd1 $1 {when a possible follow-up would be} Qb3 15. Qxb3
cxb3 16. f3 Nxa6 17. Bb5 Rfc8 18. Bc3 Nc5 19. Ne3 $16 {White managed to
completely eliminate Black's queenside initiative. He has a bishop pair and a
healthy extra pawn. The advantage is almost decisive.}) ({It turns out that
the b2-pawn needs no protection since after} 13... Qxb2 $2 14. Rb1 Qa3 15. Bc1
$18 {White is winning the queen.}) 14. Bb5 Nc7 15. Bc6 Rab8 16. O-O $1 {
Once again, White does not care about the b2-pawn. Later on, Black will waste
time to bring his queen into safety.} Qxb2 17. Qe3 $1 {[%cal Gf1b1] A key idea.
By protecting the d2-bishop, White prepares Rfb1. After kicking back the black
queen, White is ready to execute the advance e4-e5.} Qb6 18. Rfb1 Qa6 19. e5
$16 {with complete domination.}) ({Very often in Benko, when the white king
is still in the centre, Black tries to create counterplay by means of} 9... Qa5
{with two ideas - ...Nxe4 and ...Qb4. White's typical reaction is} 10. Bd2 {
when Black's can play} Qb4 (10... Nbd7 11. h3 {transposes to the next chapter.}
) 11. Bd3 $1 {White just keeps developing. The b2-cannot be taken since the
queen will be captured.} c4 12. Bc2 Bg4 {This position occurred in the game
1-0 (32) Berczes,D (2514)-Meskovs,N (2247) Stockholm 2008.} ({In this position,
} 12... Qxb2 {runs into} 13. Rb1 Qa3 14. Ne2 $1 {[%cal Gd2b4]} Qc5 15. Be3 Qc7
16. b6 $18 {with a winning advantage.}) {At this point, White should have
played} 13. a5 $1 $146 Qxb2 ({After} 13... axb5 $2 14. Na4 $18 {White is
winning the queen.}) ({Taking the knight with} 13... Bxf3 {does not change
much. The game might follow} 14. Qxf3 Nbd7 15. b6 Qxb2 16. Ra2 Qb4 17. O-O $18
{When the b6-pawn gives White a winning position.}) 14. Ra2 Qb4 15. b6 $18 {
with a decisive advantage.}) 10. Bxb5 Ba6 {This is the best way to fight
against the blockade of the queenside.} ({Fighting for the b4-square with} 
10... Na6 {does not help Black. We know that usually in such structures, the
b4-knight is useless. White obtains an advantage with simple moves.} 11. O-O
Nb4 12. Bf4 Bg4 13. Rc1 {Black cannot develop his typical queenside
counterplay. White can already start preparing the advance e4-e5.} Nh5 14. Bd2
Bd7 ({After} 14... e5 {White can play} 15. h3 Bc8 16. Re1 $1 {with the idea to
meet} Nf4 $6 {with} 17. Bxf4 exf4 18. Qd2 g5 19. e5 $18 {White's advantage is
already decisive.1-0 (24) Kazhgaleyev,M (2594)-Li,S (2502) Cappelle-la-Grande
2008}) 15. Bc4 $1 {Having more space, White refrains from exchanging pieces.
With his last move, he overprotects the d5-pawn, thus making easier the break
e4-e5.} f5 {This position, was reached in the game. 1-0 (58) Graf, A (2604)
-Becker, M (2320) Osterburg 2006. Now, the simplest would have been} 16. Re1
fxe4 17. Rxe4 Bf5 18. Ng5 Bxe4 19. Ncxe4 $16 {[%cal Gg5e6] with tremendous
compensation for the exchange. White is ready to install his knight on the
important e6-square.}) 11. Bg5 $1 {This move is a very important part of
White's strategy. By protecting the a1-rook, White planning to recapture with
a pawn in case of ...Bxb5. In this way, we reach a typical structure with a
pawn on b5. This structure was extensively covered in the section Pawn
Structures. I would like just to remind that in such structures the g5-square
is a perfect spot for the bishop. In many cases, the indirect pressure against
the e7-pawn would prevent Black from maneuvring with the f6-knight. Black has
many moves in this position, but many of them would just transpose to the next
chapter.} h6 (11... Nbd7 12. h3 {transposes to the next chapter.}) 12. Bf4 $1 {
Provoking the ...h7-h6 is useful for White. In many lines, White can make use
of the hanging h6-pawn by playing Qd2, winning an important tempo. In general,
it is good to answer ...h7-h6 with Bf4. From this position, the bishop leaves
the d2-square available for the queen and supports the advance e4-e5.} Bxb5 (
12... Nbd7 13. h3 {is a transposition.}) ({After} 12... Qa5 13. O-O {Black's
only independent continuation is} Nbd7 ({The line} 13... Qb4 14. Qe2 Bxb5 15.
axb5 Nbd7 16. h3 {leads to transposition to the next chapter.}) 14. Re1 {
[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge1e4] By protecting the e4-pawn, White intends to recapture
on b5 with a knight, thus creating the typical construction Nb5 - a4.} ({
If White insists on recapturing with a pawn, he can play} 14. h3 Bxb5 15. axb5
Qb4 16. Qe2 {transposing to the next chapter.}) {In this position, Black can
go wrong with} 14... Qb4 $2 ({Normal continuation would be} 14... Bxb5 15. Nxb5
Ng4 ({A typical mistake is} 15... Qb4 $4 16. Bd2 Qxb2 17. Bc3 $18 {when White
captures the queen.}) 16. Bd2 Qb6 17. h3 Nge5 18. Nxe5 Nxe5 19. Qc2 $16 {
White has built his desired queenside construction. Black does not have
counterplay.}) 15. Bd2 $1 {[%cal Gb5c6,Gc3b5] Underlining the vulnerable
position of the queen. White is threatening Bc6 followed by Nb5, trapping the
queen.} {Black should play} c4 {which allows} 16. Nd4 $18 {[%csl Gc6] making
use of the c6-square.}) 13. axb5 Nbd7 14. O-O {White managed to achieve a
favourable version of this well-known pawn structure. All White pieces are
well placed while Black hadn't started putting pressure on b5. The weakening ..
.h7-h6 is also in White's favour.} Qb6 15. Qe2 Rfb8 {We have been following
the game 1/2 (34) Farago, I (2510)-Halasz, T Budapest 1979. Now, the simplest
would have been} 16. e5 $1 {White's pieces are perfectly placed for this break.
It is important to know that} Nh5 {can be met with} 17. g3 $18 {White can
already consider further weakening the black king by means of e5-e6. White's
advantage is already decisive.} *

