1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 a6 5. e3 g6 6. Nc3 Bg7 7. Nf3 O-O 8. a4 d6
9. e4 Nbd7 {In my opinion, this is Black's most challenging move order. Before
taking on b5, he is waiting for White to develop the f1-bishop. At the same
time, the move ...Nbd7 fits very well into the classical Benko concepts. White
faces a choice now. I have decided to opt for the rare} 10. h3 $1 {By making a
useful move, White waits for the move ...axb5. Since Black cannot open the
centre by means of ...e7-e6 (the d6-pawn will be hanging after dxe6), White
can afford to make such moves. At the same time, taking the g4-square under
control is important because Black can no longer execute the typical manoeuvre.
..Ng4-e5. If we are going to enter a structure with a white pawn on b5, there
will be two good squares for the dark-squared bishop - g5 and f4 (this is
explained in the section Pawn Structures). In this position, I prefer to start
with Bg5 and after provoking ...h7-h6 settle for Bf4. In such a case, the move
10.h3 will be very useful since moves like ...Nh5 or ...g6-g5 can always be
met with Bh2.  In order to understand the advantages of the move 10.h3, please
take a look at my annotations to the alternatives 10.Bd2 and 10.Bg5.} ({
In the beginning, I was trying to make the move} 10. Bd2 {work. Now, in
response to ...axb5 White can even take with a pawn. In the structure with a
pawn on b5, however, the d2-square is not very good for the bishop. White
would prefer to keep it available for the manoeuvre Nd2-c4. In order to
illustrate my point, I provide some brief analysis.} axb5 11. axb5 {This was
the initial idea behind 10.Bd2.} ({After} 11. Bxb5 {, Black should remove the
b5-bishop with} Ba6 {when the following sequence is possible:} 12. O-O Bxb5 13.
axb5 Rxa1 14. Qxa1 Qb6 {[%cal Gf8b8,Gf6e8,Ge8c7] Black is planning to put
pressure on b5 by means of ...Rb8 followed by the typical manoeuvre...Ne8-c7.
Had the bishop not been on d2, White would have been in time to carry out the
manoeuvre Nd2-c4. Therefore, I focused on} 15. Bg5 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4] planning
Nd2-c4 and preventing ...Ne8-c7. Black, however, can play} h6 16. Bf4 $1 {
Besides g5, f4 is another very good spot for the bishop in this structure. In
such positions, Black should always reckon with the central break e4-e5.} ({
After} 16. Bh4 g5 17. Bg3 Nh5 {White will have to part with his dark-squared
bishop. At the same time, Black will follow with ...Rb8, increasing the
pressure on the b5-pawn.}) 16... Kh7 $1 {Overprotecting the h6-pawn.} ({
The immediate} 16... Rb8 {can be answered with} 17. Qc1 Kh7 18. e5 {As we know,
this is a typical idea in such structures. White Black is trying to regain the
pawn, White often strikes in the centre.}) 17. Re1 {[%cal Ge4e5] White is
planning the thematic e4-e5.} ({The immediate} 17. e5 {runs into} Nh5 {
regaining the pawn.}) 17... Nh5 $1 18. Be3 {Unfortunately, the bishop is
forced to leave the diagonal h2-b8. If White had previously played h2-h3, the
h2-square would have been available for the bishop.} Rb8 ({By giving his
dark-squared bishop, Black can immediately regain the pawn. Such an exchange,
however, leaves the kingside vulnerable. For example -} 18... Bxc3 19. bxc3
Qxb5 20. Qc1 Rb8 ({Keeping the pawn with} 20... g5 {does not solve the
problems. After} 21. Qc2 $16 {White keeps his advantage because of the
vulnerable black king.}) 21. Bxh6 Nhf6 22. Bg5 {Black's compensation for the
pawn is not enough.}) {The following sequence seems pretty logical to me.} 19.
Nd2 {Played with the idea to meet 20.Nc4 with 20...Bxc3 followed by 21...Qxb5.}
Qb7 20. Qa2 {[%cal Ge1a1]} Nhf6 {[%csl Re3][%cal Gf6e8,Ge8c7,Gf6g4] Black is
going for the typical maneuver ...Nf6-e8-c7. Meanwhile, he is creating the
threat of ...Ng4.} 21. h3 Ne8 22. Ra1 Nc7 23. Qb3 Bxc3 24. bxc3 Nxb5 25. Nc4 {
Even though, White can still keep some pressure due to his space advantage,
Black's counterplay along the b-file should be enough for equality.}) 11...
Rxa1 12. Qxa1 {It turns out that, Black has use his advantage in the
development to open the centre with} e6 $1 {After} 13. dxe6 fxe6 {[%cal Gd6d5]
planning ...d6-d5 the position is pretty unclear. 1-0 (36) Gasanov, E (2550)
-Shukh, N (2377) Belgorod 2008}) ({Since, one of the main drawbacks of the move
10.Bd2 is taking the d2-square from the knight (as mentioned above, in
structures with a pawn on b5, White often opts for the manoeuvre Nd2-c4), I
tried the immediate} 10. Bg5 {In this case, however, Black can start
immediately chasing the bishop with} h6 11. Bf4 g5 12. Bg3 ({The alternative} 
12. Be3 {can be countered with} Ng4) 12... Nh5 {Once again, White will be
forced to part with his dark-squared bishop.}) 10... axb5 {Black cannot delay
this move forever. Of course, we shall take a look at the alternatives.} ({
Typically} 10... Qa5 $2 {is well met by} 11. Bd2 {The main line goes} Qb4 12.
Qc2 Bb7 ({Nothing changes} 12... axb5 13. Bxb5 {when Black has no compensation
for the pawn.}) 13. b3 Nb6 14. Rb1 axb5 15. Bd3 $1 {Not the only move but the
most elegant one. By protecting the e4-pawn, White is threatening Nxb5 with
the idea of trapping the queen.} c4 16. bxc4 Qc5 17. Rxb5 {White obtained a
decisive advantage in 1-0 (18) Volkov, S (2613)-Akshayraj, K (2508) Abu Dhabi
2013}) ({The premature} 10... Ne8 $6 {can be answered with} 11. Bg5 axb5 12.
axb5 Rxa1 13. Qxa1 $16 {with a clear advantage for White.}) ({Preparing ...
e7-e6 with} 10... Re8 {is not effective in this position. I suggest the normal}
11. Bg5 {when} e6 $2 {runs into} 12. dxe6 Rxe6 13. Bc4 Re8 14. O-O $18 {
With a totally winning position.}) 11. Bxb5 Ba6 12. Bg5 $1 {This is the point
of White's entire concept. We are now ready to recapture on b5 with a pawn. In
this case, the bishop will be on the perfect g5-square. Additionally, since
White had played h2-h3, the g5-bishop can be transferred to h2 in a case of
necessity. Black's counterplay is far from obvious.} Bxb5 {Black immediately
clarifies the structure.} ({It is also possible to start with} 12... h6 {
which should always be countered with} 13. Bf4 $1 {A possible line would be}
Qa5 14. O-O Bxb5 15. axb5 Qb4 16. Qe2 Nb6 ({With h2-h3 had been played,} 16...
Nh5 {can be answered with} 17. Bh2 {Winning the pawn back by means of} Rxa1 ({
After} 17... Bxc3 18. bxc3 Qxc3 {White can play} 19. Ra6 $16 {[%cal Ge4e5]
making use of the a6-outpost. The break e4-e5 is coming.}) 18. Rxa1 Bxc3 19.
bxc3 Qxc3 20. Ra7 Nhf6 21. Bf4 $16 {White has a clear advantage due to the
strong passed pawn, piece activity and Black's vulnerable king.}) 17. Bh2 {
Escaping from the opposition with the queen and preparing e4-e5.} ({An
alternative is} 17. Ra6 {which is typical for this pawn structure,} Na4 ({
White keeps his edge also after} 17... Rxa6 18. bxa6 Qa5 {[%cal Gf8a8] Black
is planning to win the pawn back with ...Ra8. Meanwhile, White can strike in
the centre.} 19. Rd1 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge4e5]} Ra8 20. e5 dxe5 21. Nxe5 Qxa6 22.
Qe3 $14) 18. e5 Qxf4 19. exf6 Bxf6 20. Ne4 Bg7 21. b3 $14 {Despite the equal
material, the strong b5-pawn gives White an advantage. Black should reckon
with the manoeuvre Ned2-c4.}) 17... Qc4 ({In a case of} 17... Nfd7 {White can
play} 18. Rab1 {[%cal Ge4e5] protecting the b2-pawn and preparing to follow
with e4-e5.}) {At this point, White can settle for the following sequence} 18.
Qxc4 Nxc4 19. e5 Nd7 20. exd6 exd6 21. Ra6 Nxb2 22. Rxd6 Ra7 23. Nd1 $16 {
White is clearly better due to his healthy extra pawn.}) 13. axb5 h6 14. Bf4
Rxa1 {Driving the queen away from the centre is Black's most natural reaction.}
({Useless is} 14... Nb6 {since later Black will not be able to put pressure on
b5.} 15. O-O Rxa1 16. Qxa1 {It is clear that Black does not have enough
compensation for the pawn. 1/2 (33) Tonon, A (2175)-Mocchi, T (2352) Nova Gorica
2001}) 15. Qxa1 Ne8 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gd8b8,Ge8c7] This seems to be more flexible
continuation. Afterwards, Black can attack the b5-pawn by means of ...Qb6/b8
followed by Nc7.} ({Another possibility is} 15... Qb6 16. O-O Rb8 {[%cal Gf6e8,
Ge8c7] Black is planning to manoeuvre...Ne8-c7. Therefore, White
should play energetically.} 17. Qc1 $1 {Bringing the queen back into the game
with a tempo. We can see now the importance of provoking ...h7-h6.} Kh7 ({
In the event of} 17... g5 {, White can immediately strike with} 18. e5 $1 {
when after} Ne8 19. e6 fxe6 20. dxe6 Nf8 21. Bg3 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Qxb5 23. h4 $16
{White has a clear advantage due to the weakened black king.}) 18. e5 Ne8 19.
Re1 $16 {As often happens in this structure, White's initiative in the centre
prevents Black from winning the pawn back.}) ({Another idea is} 15... Qb8 {
planning to follow with ...Ne8-c7, without allowing Qa8.} 16. O-O Ne8 17. Qc1
$1 {Again, the same typical motif.} Kh7 ({Sacrificing the pawn with} 17... Nc7
18. Bxh6 Nxb5 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Ne2 Nf6 21. Qe3 Nc7 22. b3 $16 {leaves Black
without sufficient compensation for the pawn. White can even consider
developing a kingside initiative.}) 18. Qe3 Nc7 19. Qd3 Qb7 {[%cal Gf8b8,Gc7b5]
White can do nothing to protect the b5-pawn. Therefore, he puts his two cents
