1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. d5 b5 4. cxb5 {In this chapter, we are going to deal
with some possible deviations on move 4. Even though these moves are not
popular and challenging, we are going to examine them for the sake of
completeness.} {Sometimes, Black immediately attacks the centre with} e6 {
Nevertheless, I don't think that Black is prepared for such an early
confrontation. The main line goes} ({Some Benko players delay ...a7-a6 by
giving priority to the kingside development.} 4... g6 {In this case, I suggest}
5. Nc3 Bg7 6. e4 d6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. a4 {Now, Black cannot delay ...a7-a6 any
longer. In this case, we are going to follow the same strategy as in the main
line. This situation is even more favourable for White since he didn't waste
time on playing e2-e3 and then e3-e4.}) 5. Nc3 exd5 6. Nxd5 Bb7 7. Nxf6+ Qxf6
8. Nf3 d5 {Black hopes that his central pawns and the semi-open e-file will be
enough compensation for the pawn. Nevertheless, he is not well-developed while
White didn't make a concession so far.} ({Strangely enough, the less popular} 
8... a6 {makes more sense than 8...d5. The game might continue} 9. bxa6 Nxa6
10. g3 {When you have a choice, it is better to put the bishop on g2 in order to
protect the king and neutralize the pressure created by the b7-bishop.} Be7 11.
Bg2 Be4 {[%csl Rd1][%cal Gf6f5,Ge4c2] The idea behind this move is to play ...
Qf5 eventually followed by ...Bc2. White's play is pretty straightforward.} 12.
O-O Qf5 13. Bf4 O-O 14. Bd6 $1 {An important move. In order to remove the
blockade, Black should play} Qe6 {when White's best is} 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Nh4 {
White is planning to exchange the bishops. After this exchange, it will be
difficult for Black to prove his compensation for the pawn.} h6 {Black waits
for White to make the exchange. In this case, the queen will occupy the
central e4-square.} ({Worse is} 16... Bxg2 {which was seen in the game 1-0 (27)
Husemann, A (2077)-Moreira, J (1929) LSS email 2011. Here, White should have
played} 17. Nxg2 $16 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gg2f4,Gf1d1] with a clear advantage. He can
now start pressing along the d-file by making simple moves such as Qd2
followed by Rfd1 and Nf4. The knight could eventually occupy the d5-square.})
17. Bxe4 Qxe4 18. Rc1 $14 {This position occurred in the game 1/2 (31) Nichols,
S (2240)-Keevil,P (2154) LSS email 2011. I don't believe that Black's activity
provides enough compensation for the pawn since White has no weaknesses. In
the abovementioned correspondence game, Black managed to hold this position,
but in practical chess White's play is easier.}) 9. g3 Bd6 ({After} 9... Nd7
10. Bg2 Bd6 {we transpose to the main line.}) 10. Bg2 O-O (10... Nd7 11. O-O
O-O {is another transposition.}) 11. O-O Nd7 {We have finally reached the
critical position of the variation.} ({In 7 games, Black opted for} 11... a6 $2
{which is already a decisive mistake. Instead of the 12.bxa6 which was played
in 4 games, White should opt for the powerful} 12. Ng5 $1 {after which Black
cannot hold his central pawns. For example, after} axb5 13. Bxd5 Bxd5 14. Qxd5
$18 {White was winning in 1-0 (40) Batchimeg, T (2194)-Enkhtuul, A (1834)
Ulaanbaatar 2011.}) {At this point, White's main move is 12.Qc2. This
continuation, however, seems a bit passive to me. Instead, I would suggest the
rare} 12. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Ge2e4,Gd2c4,Gg2b7] This move demonstrates a
powerful concept. White has two main ideas - striking in the centre with e2-e4
or making use of the opposition of the bishop by playing Nc4. In the latter
case, Black's d5-pawn would be vulnerable.} Nb6 {Black overprotects the
d5-pawn and prevents Nc4.} ({The natural} 12... Rfe8 $2 {runs into} 13. Nc4 $1
Nb6 14. Nxd6 Qxd6 15. a4 $18 {A typical way of playing against a knight on b6.
White has a decisive advantage due to his extra pawn and bishop pair.
Additionally, Black's centre is vulnerable.}) ({The move} 12... Qe6 {was
played in the game 0-1 (15) Dimukhametov,A (2242)-Gavariev,R (2336) Nabereznye
Chelny 2010. At this point, White missed a beautiful idea -} 13. Nc4 $1 {
[%csl Rb7][%cal Gc4d6,Gc4a5,Ga5b7] Besides attacking the d6-bishop, the knight
is also heading to a5. In this position, the natural} Bc7 {would be answered
with the powerful} 14. Bf4 $1 Bxf4 15. Na5 $1 {This beautiful intermediate
move is the point of White's previous play. The game might continue} Qb6 16.
Nxb7 Nf6 17. Bxd5 Be5 18. Rc1 $16 {when White is clearly better.}) ({After} 
12... Rad8 {which occurred in 1/2 (24) Rizzo,G (2089)-Delfino,L (2078) Bari
2005, White could have played the typical} 13. Nc4 Bb8 ({In the event of} 13...
Bc7 $6 {White can put pressure on d5 by means of} 14. Ne3 $1 {Of course, as
always,} Nb6 {runs into} 15. a4 $18) 14. a4 $16 {Black has absolutely no
compensation for the pawn.}) 13. e4 Be5 {We have been following the game 1/2 
(15) Grandelius,N (2388)-Ivanov,M (2492) Ballerup 2008. In this position,
White could have settled for the typical} 14. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5] playing
against the b6-knight and trying the weaken the d5-pawn. After} Rad8 15. a5 Nc8
16. Qc2 $16 {White's advantage is obvious.} *

