{What is the key idea in this position?} 1. Bd3 $1 {[%cal Gd1c2,Gc1d2,Ga2a4,
Ga4a5] A very subtle move. White improves the position of his light-squared
bishop and prepares Bd2 (since the bishop is no longer on b5, White can always
answer ...Qxb2 with Rb1). After many hours of analysis, I realized that
White's ideal setup is Bd3, Bd2, and Qc2. Afterwards, White can start
advancing his a-pawn. Additionally, depending on the concrete circumstances,
White can attack the pawn centre by means of e3-e4 or b2-b4 (when trying to
weaken the d4-square). Black's ...d5-d4 is usually answered with Be4 or e3-e4.
White plays Bc3 in positions where the advance ...d5-d4 is not favourable for
Black.} *

